aproape-de-un-gol-de-generic-in-meciul|title=Coman a fost aproape de un gol de generic \u00een meciul \u00eenaintea c\u0103ruia a primit \u0219i trofeul de \"Fotbalistul lunii\" februarie|trans-title=Coman was inches away from scoring an amazing goal after he received the \"Player of the Month\" trophy for February|publisher=Digi Sport|language=Romanian|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Liga I]] Team of the Season: [[2016\u201317 Liga I|2016\u201317]], [[2018\u201319 Liga I|2018\u201319]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{RomanianSoccer|4222/florinel-teodor-coman}}\n*{{UEFA player|250078023}}\n\n{{FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coman, Florinel}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Br\u0103ila]]\n[[Category:Romanian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba players]]\n[[Category:FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti players]]\n[[Category:Romania youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romania under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romania international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "8Dodo8", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florinel_Coman"}
{"title_page": "Iran\u2013Pakistan relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Islamic Republic of Pakistan}}\n{{cleanup|reason=Poor writing.|date=December 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox bilateral relations|Iran\u2013Pakistan|Iran|Pakistan|map=Iran Pakistan Locator.png}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n\nAfter [[Pakistan]] [[Partition of India|gained its independence]] in August 1947, [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iran]] was one of the first countries to [[Diplomatic recognition|recognize]] its sovereign status.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Pakistan's relations with Iran became strained at times due to sectarian tensions, as Pakistani [[Shia Islam|Shi'a]] [[Muslims]] claimed that they were being [[Shia\u2013Sunni relations|discriminated]] against under the [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]-biased [[Zia ul-Haq's Islamization|Islamization]] program being imposed throughout Pakistan by the [[military dictatorship]] [[Government of Pakistan|government]] of [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wLtA_J3VUt4C&pg=PA144&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIGTAA#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran's Foreign Policy in the Post-Soviet Era: Resisting the New International Order|last=Hunter|first=Shireen|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2010|isbn=9780313381942|location=|pages=144|quote=Since then, Pakistan's sectarian tensions have been a major irritant in Iranian-Pakistan relations.|via=}}</ref> [[Iran]] and [[Saudi Arabia]] (considered the \"leading authority\" of Shi'a and Sunni Muslims, respectively) used Pakistan as a battleground for [[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict|their proxy sectarian war]], and Pakistan's support for the [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi]] [[Taliban]] organization in Afghanistan [[Afghan Civil War (1992\u20131996)|by the 1990s]] became a problem for Shi'a Iran, which opposed a [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|Taliban-controlled Afghanistan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ceg-kSmft94C&pg=PA159&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Explaining Pakistan\u2019s Foreign Policy: Escaping India|last=Pande|first=Aparna|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2011|isbn=9781136818943|location=|pages=159|quote=Both Saudi Arabia and Iran used Pakistan as a battleground for their proxy war for the 'hearts and minds' of Pakistani Wahhabis and Non muslims with the resultant rise in sectarian tensions in Pakistan. The rise of the Taliban in Afghanistan in the 1990s further strained Pakistan-Iran relations. Pakistan's support of the Wahhabi Pashtun organization created problems for Shia Iran for whom a Taliban-controlled Afghanistan was a nightmare.|via=}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, both countries continue to cooperate economically [[Sanctions against Iran|where possible]] and are forming alliances in a number of areas of mutual interest, such as fighting the [[Illegal drug trade|drug trade]] along their border and combating the [[Insurgency in Balochistan|insurgency in the Balochistan region]]. Iran has also expressed an interest in joining the [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor|China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC)]].<ref>http://www.dawn.com/news/1285404</ref><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Iran-keen-to-become-part-of-China-Pak-Economic-Corridor/articleshow/54462795.cms</ref>\n\nPakistan is one of the only countries where Iran is viewed positively as per the polls conducted by [[Pew Research Center]]. Polls have consistently shown that a very high proportion of Pakistanis view their western neighbor positively.<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|last=Max Fisher|title=Iran is popular in Pakistan, overwhelmingly disliked everywhere else|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/01/11/iran-is-popular-in-pakistan-overwhelmingly-disliked-everywhere-else/|accessdate=19 March 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=11 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2015/06/18/irans-global-image-mostly-negative/|title=Iran\u2019s Global Image Mostly Negative|last=Zainulbhai|first=Hani|last2=Wike|first2=Richard|date=18 June 2015|website=PEW Research Center|publisher=|access-date=5 January 2017|quote=Even in Pakistan, opinion of Iran has somewhat soured, with negative ratings increasing from 8% to 16% over the past year.}}</ref> [[Supreme Leader of Iran]] [[Ali Khamenei|Ayatollah Khamenei]] has also called for the [[Pan-Islamism|sympathy and assistance]] of many [[Muslim world|Muslim nations]], including Pakistan.<ref>http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/as-modi-embraces-israel-irans-ayatollah-khamenei-urges-support-for-oppressed-muslims-of-kashmir/articleshow/59455486.cms</ref>\n\n== Country comparison ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n\n! Common Name !! [[Pakistan]] !! [[Iran]]\n\n|-\n! Official Name !! Islamic Republic of Pakistan !! Islamic Republic of Iran\n\n|-\n| Coat of Arms\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:State emblem of Pakistan.svg|130px]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:Emblem of Iran.svg|130px]]\n\n|-\n| Flag\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Pakistan|size=130px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Iran|size=130px|text=none}}\n\n|-\n| [[List of countries and dependencies by area|Area]]\n| 881,913&nbsp;km\u00b2 (340,509 sq mi)\n| 1,648,195&nbsp;km\u00b2 (636,372 sq mi)\n\n|-\n| [[List of countries by population|Population]]\n| 212,286,286<ref name=census>{{cite web |url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk |title=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/content/provisional-summary-results-5th-population-and-housing-census-2017-0 |website=pbscensus.gov.pk |access-date=2 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015113737/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/ |archive-date=15 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 82,531,700\n\n|-\n| [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density|Population Density]]\n| 244.4/km\u00b2 (633/sq mi)\n| 48/km\u00b2 (124.3/sq mi)\n\n|-\n| [[List of national capitals|Capital]]\n\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| [[Tehran]]\n|-\n| Largest Metropolitan Area\n| [[Karachi]] (16,051,521)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2017-08-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| [[Tehran]] (23,000,000)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913144137/http://citypopulation.de/world/Agglomerations.html|title=Major Agglomerations of the World - Population Statistics and Maps|date=2018-09-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| Government\n| [[Federalism|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|Parliamentary]] [[Republic]]\n|[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Presidential system|Presidential]] [[Republic]]\n\n|-\n| Current Leader\n| [[Imran Khan]]\n| [[Ali Khamenei]]\n|-\n|Official Languages\n| [[Urdu]]\n|[[Persian language|Farsi (Persian)]]\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP|GDP (nominal)]]\n| $284.21 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=68&pr.y=12&sy=2017&ey=2024&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=564&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC,PCPIPCH&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| $463.08 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=43&pr.y=15&sy=2017&ey=2021&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=429&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|GDP (PPP)]]\n| $1.202 Trillion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=75&pr.y=3&sy=2017&ey=2024&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=564&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| $1.471 Trillion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=43&pr.y=15&sy=2017&ey=2021&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=429&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|GDP (nominal) per Capita]]\n| $1,388\n| $5,820\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP (PPP) per Capita]]\n| $5,872\n| $18,504\n|-\n| [[List of countries by Human Development Index|Human Development Index]]\n| {{increase}} 0.560 (<span style=\"color:#fc0;\">Medium</span>)\n| {{increase}} 0.798 (<span style=\"color:#009900;\">High</span>)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by military expenditures|Military Expenditures]]\n| $11.4 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalfirepower.com/country-military-strength-detail.asp?country_id=pakistan|title=2020 Pakistan Military Strength|website=www.globalfirepower.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| $19.6 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalfirepower.com/country-military-strength-detail.asp?country_id=iran|title=2020 Iran Military Strength|website=www.globalfirepower.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Antiquity ==\n{{Main|Achaemenid conquest of the Indus Valley|Persianate society|Indo-Persian culture}}\n[[File:Tribute in the Achaemenid Empire.jpg|thumb|Map showing the distribution of Achaemenid tax revenues, according to the [[Greeks|Greek]] historian [[Herodotus]]]]\nThe regions that comprise modern-day [[Iran]] and [[Pakistan]] have been under the rule of contiguous [[Eurasia|Eurasian]] polities at various points in history, as Pakistan straddles an intermediary zone between the [[Iranian Plateau]] and [[Indian subcontinent]]. The Persian [[Achaemenid Empire]], which spanned the area between the [[Balkans]] and the [[Indus River]] at its height, conquered the regions comprising of [[Balochistan|Baluchistan]], [[Sindh]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and [[Punjab, Pakistan|western Punjab]] during the reign of [[Darius the Great|Darius I]]. \n\n==Relations during the Cold War==\n{{Main|Cold War (1947\u201353)|Cold War (1953\u201362)}}\n\n[[Pahlavi dynasty|Imperial Iran]] maintained close relations with [[Pakistan]] during much of the [[Cold War]], owing to their mutual alliance with the [[United States]]-led [[Western Bloc]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=24\u201325|quote=Iran's relations with Pakistan and India in the mid-20th century were the mirror image of that which exists today. Whereas Tehran now sees New Delhi as a natural partner, it maintained much closer ties with Islamabad throughout most of the Cold War.|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\">{{cite web|last=Officials|title=Pak-Iran Relations Since Islamic Revolution: Genisis of Cooperation and Competition|url=http://www.iranembassy.pk/en/political-section/592-pak-iran-relations-since-islamic-revolution-genisis-of-cooperatio-and-competition.html|publisher=Embassy of Iran, Islamabad|accessdate=25 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410121859/http://www.iranembassy.pk/en/political-section/592-pak-iran-relations-since-islamic-revolution-genisis-of-cooperatio-and-competition.html|archivedate=10 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Iran was the first country to recognise Pakistan as an independent state, and the [[List of monarchs of Persia|Shah of Iran]] was the first head of any state to come on an official [[state visit]] to Pakistan (in March 1950).<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Since 1947, [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]], the [[Quaid-i-Azam|founder of Pakistan]], had successfully advocated a policy of fostering cordial relations with Iran in particular and the [[Muslim world]] in general.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Despite [[Shia\u2013Sunni relations|Shi'a-Sunni divisions]], desires for a [[Pan-Islamism|pan-Islamic identity]] became an important factor in shaping Iranian\u2013Pakistani relations, especially after the [[Iranian Revolution|1979 Islamic Revolution in Iran]].\n\n[[File:Fpbutto.jpg|thumb|200px|left|[[President of Pakistan|Pakistani President]] [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] meeting with [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iranian Queen]] [[Farah Pahlavi]], 1972]]\n\nIn May 1950, a treaty of friendship was signed by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Liaquat Ali Khan]] and the Shah of Iran. Some of the clauses of the treaty of friendship had wider geopolitical significance.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\">{{cite web|last=Pant|first=Harsh V.|title=Pakistan and Iran's Dysfunctional Relationship|url=http://www.meforum.org/2119/pakistan-and-irans-dysfunctional-relationship|work=Middle East Quarterly|accessdate=28 November 2012|date=Spring 2009}}</ref> Pakistan found a natural partner in Iran after the [[Government of India|Indian government]] chose to support [[President of Egypt|Egyptian President]] [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]], who was seeking to export a [[Pan-Arabism|pan-Arab ideology]] that threatened many of the more traditional Arab monarchies, a number of which were allied with the Shah.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Harsh V. Pant, a foreign policy writer, noted that Iran was a natural ally and model for Pakistan for other reasons as well. Both countries granted each other [[Most favoured nation|MFN]] status for trade purposes; the Shah offered Iranian oil and gas to Pakistan on generous terms, and the [[Imperial Iranian Armed Forces|Iranian]] and [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani militaries]] extensively cooperated to suppress the [[Insurgency in Balochistan|rebel movement in Baluchistan]].<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> During the [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Shah]]'s era, Iran moved closer to Pakistan in many fields.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Pakistan, Iran, and Turkey joined the United States-sponsored [[Baghdad Pact|Central Treaty Organization]], which extended a defensive alliance along the [[Soviet Union|Soviet Union's]] southern perimeter.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Iran played an important role in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]], providing Pakistan with nurses, medical supplies, and a gift of 5,000 tons of petroleum. Iran also indicated that it was considering an embargo on oil supplies to [[India]] for the duration of the armed conflict.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The Indian government believed that Iran had blatantly favored Pakistan.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> After the suspension of American military aid to Pakistan, Iran was reported to have purchased ninety [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabrejet]] fighter planes from [[West Germany]], and subsequently delivered them to Pakistan.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\nAlthough Pakistan's decision to join the Central Treaty Organization (CENTO) in 1955 was largely motivated by its [[Indo-Pakistani wars and conflicts|security imperatives regarding India]], Pakistan did not sign on until Iran was satisfied that the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] was not going to obstruct the nationalization of British oil companies in Iran.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> According to Dr. Mujtaba Razvi, Pakistan likely would not have joined CENTO had Iran been negatively affected during these events.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\nIran had again played a vital role for Pakistan in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]], this time supplying military equipment as well as diplomatic support against India. The Shah described the Indian attack as aggression and interference in [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Pakistan's domestic affairs]];<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> in an interview with a Parisian newspaper he openly acknowledged that \"We are one hundred percent behind Pakistan\".<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> [[Prime Minister of Iran|Iranian Prime Minister]] [[Amir-Abbas Hoveida]] followed suit, saying that \"Pakistan has been subjected to violence and force.\"<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> The Iranian leadership repeatedly expressed its opposition to the dismemberment of Pakistan, fearing it would adversely affect the domestic stability and security of Iran<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> by encouraging [[Kurdish separatism in Iran|Kurdish]] and [[Baloch nationalism|Baloch separatists]] to rise up against the Iranian government.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> In the same vein, Iran attempted to justify its supplying arms to Pakistan on the grounds that, in its desperation, Pakistan might fall into the lap of the Chinese.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> On the other hand, Iran changed its foreign priorities after making a move to maintain good relations with India.\n\nThe subsequent breakup of Pakistan in December 1971 convinced Iran that extraordinary effort was needed to protect the stability and territorial integrity of its eastern flank. With the emergence of [[Bangladesh]] as a separate state, the \"[[Two-nation theory (Pakistan)|Two-Nation Theory]]/[[Pakistan Movement]]\" received a severe blow and questions arose in the Iranian establishment as to whether the residual western part of Pakistan could hold together and remain a single country.<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\">{{cite journal|last=Alam|first=Shah|title=Iran\u2013Pakistan Relations: Political and Strategic Dimensions|journal=Strategic Analysis|date=20 December 2004|volume=28|issue=4|pages=20|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:tQHaWA6pkXgJ:www.idsa.in/system/files/strategicanalysis_salam_1204.pdf+Iran+pakistan+relations+1970s&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgpvNr5msxhiEG93UEzp5nCtujak6TcZZva0ITbwY1sSSy2AnSKDtEDgI32eOz_6bX_veJ06nb6ewBMEQ_iynP0g8LM3mldXkK7agUZcotXgvseoatRnlYsiR1U_26SctfIZ1SN&sig=AHIEtbTCi4g0Ksw-WOFlhcwrichNsu_cpA|accessdate=26 November 2012|publisher=\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|language=English|format=google docs.|doi=10.1080/09700160408450157}}</ref> Events of this period caused significant perceptional changes in Tehran regarding Pakistan.\n\nWhen widespread [[1970s Operation in Balochistan|armed insurgency]] broke out in Pakistan's [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan province]] in 1973, Iran, fearing the insurgency might spill over into its own [[Sistan and Baluchestan Province|Sistan and Baluchistan Province]], offered large-scale support.<ref>[[Foreign Policy Centre]], \"On the Margins of History\", (2008), p.35</ref> The Iranians provided Pakistan with military hardware (including thirty [[Bell AH-1 Cobra|AH-1 Cobra]] attack helicopters), intelligence, and $200 million in aid.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4182151.stm|title=Pakistan risks new battlefront|accessdate=8 April 2006|date=17 January 2005|work=BBC News}}</ref> The government of then-[[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] declared its belief that, as in the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|1971 Bangladesh Liberation War]], India was once again behind the unrest and uprising of rebels in the Balochistan region. However, the Indian government denied any involvement, and claimed that it was fearful of further [[Balkanization|balkanisation]] of the [[Indian subcontinent|subcontinent]].<ref name=\"BBC News\" /> After three years of fighting the uprising was majorly suppressed.<ref name=\"BBC News\" />\n[[File:Mohammad Ali Jenah Iran stamp.jpg|right|thumb|1976 Iranian postage stamp featuring Pakistan's founder, [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah|Muhammed Ali Jinnah]]]]\n\nIn addition to military aid, the Shah of Iran offered considerable developmental aid to Pakistan, including oil and gas on preferential terms.<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\" /> Pakistan was a [[developing country]] and [[Power (international relations)|small power]], while Iran, in the 1960-70s, had the world's fifth largest military and a strong industrial base, and was the clear, undisputed regional superpower.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\">{{cite web |title=1971 war and Iran|url=http://iranembassy.pk/en/political-section/591-pak-iran-relation-since-1947.html|publisher=1971 war and Iran|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/panorama/hi/front_page/newsid_8084000/8084871.stm|title=BBC - Panorama - Iran Archives: Oil Barrels and the Gun|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> However, Iran's total dependence on the United States at that time for its economic development and military build-up had won it [[Arab League\u2013Iran relations|hostility]] from the [[Arab world]].<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> Tensions arose in 1974, when [[Pahlavi dynasty|Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] refused to attend the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|Islamic Conference]] in [[Lahore]] because [[History of Libya under Muammar Gaddafi|Libyan]] leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] had been invited to it, despite the known hostility between Libya and Iran.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> In 1976, Iran again played a vital and influential role by facilitating a rapprochement between Pakistan and [[Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\nIran's reaction to India's surprise 1974 [[Nuclear weapons testing|nuclear test]] detonation (codenamed ''[[Smiling Buddha]]'') was muted.<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\" /> During a state visit to Iran in 1977, Bhutto tried to persuade Pahlavi to support Pakistan's own clandestine [[Pakistan and weapons of mass destruction|atomic bomb project]].<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\" /> Although the Shah's response is not known, there are indications that he refused to oblige Bhutto.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" />\n\nIn July 1977, following political agitation by an opposition alliance, Bhutto was forced out of office in a [[1977 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The new [[Zia regime|military dictatorship government]], under [[General officer|General]] [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]], was ideologically [[Political Islam|ultraconservative]] and religiously oriented ([[Sunni Islam|Sunni-biased]]) in its nature and approach in contrast to the more secular Iran at the time.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\n===Relationship after the 1979 Iranian revolution===\n\nThe 1979 [[Iranian Revolution]] transformed Pakistan and Iran into rivals instead of partners.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=24|quote=The 1979 Iranian Revolution greatly altered the nature of Iran-Pakistan relations, transforming the two countries into rivals rather than partners.|via=}}</ref> Bhutto's ouster was followed a half year later by the [[Iranian Revolution]] and overthrow of the [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Shah of Iran]]. Iran's new Supreme Leader, the [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], withdrew the country from CENTO and ended its association with the United States.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The religiously influenced military government of Zia-ul-Haq and the Islamic Revolution in Iran suited one another well, and as such there was no diplomatic and political cleavage between them.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> In 1979, Pakistan was one of the first countries in the world to recognize the revolutionary regime in Iran. Responding swiftly to this revolutionary change, [[Foreign Minister of Pakistan]] [[Agha Shahi]] immediately undertook a state visit to Tehran, meeting with his Iranian [[Foreign Minister of Iran|counterpart]] [[Karim Sanjabi]] on 10 March 1979.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Both expressed confidence that Iran and Pakistan were going to march together to a brighter future.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The next day, Agha Shahi held talks with the [[Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini]], in which developments in the region were discussed.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> On 11 April 1979, Zia famously declared that \"Khomeini is a symbol of Islamic insurgence\".<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Reciprocating President Zia's sentiments, Imam Khomeini, in his letter, called for Muslim unity.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> He declared: \"Ties with Pakistan are based on Islam.\"<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> By 1981, however, Pakistan, under [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]], had once again formed close ties with the United States, a position it has remained in since.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\n====Iranian influence on Pakistan's Shia population====\nIranian leaders had sought to extend their sphere of influence in Pakistan and to counter Saudi influence. As such, a pro-Iranian stance amongst many politicized Pakistani Shias is widespread. Many Pakistani Shia websites are filled with writings advocating the Khamanei regime.<ref>https://books.google.ca/books?id=t6aKCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA312&dq=pro-iranian+shias+in+pakistan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJu4r0z97mAhV0dc0KHds4A-YQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=pro-iranian%20shias%20in%20pakistan&f=false</ref>\n\n===Pakistani support for Iran during the Iran\u2013Iraq war===\n{{Main|Iran\u2013Iraq War|Pakistan and the Iran\u2013Iraq War}}\nWhile Pakistan remained neutral during the Iran-Iraq War, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's attempts to export the Iranian revolution fueled tensions between Pakistan's Sunnis and Shias.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=24|quote=While Pakistan remained neutral during the Iran-Iraq War, which threatened the fledgling Islamic Republic's existence, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's efforts to export the Iranian Revolution fueled tensions in Pakistan between its Sunni majority and sizable Shia minority.|via=}}</ref> The militancy of Shia inspired by revolutionary Iran left many Pakistani Sunni feeling deeply threatened.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> President Zia, despite his pro-Saudi and anti-Shia sentiments,<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> had to manage his country's security carefully, knowing that Pakistan risked being dragged into a war with its closest neighbor because of its alliance with the United States.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> In support of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]], formed in 1981, around 40,000 personnel of the Pakistan Armed Forces were stationed in [[Saudi Arabia]] to reinforce the internal and external security of the region.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> Although high-ranking members of Pakistan Armed Forces strongly objected to the killing of Shia pilgrims in the [[1987 Mecca incident]] in Saudi Arabia, Zia did not issue any orders to Pakistan Armed Forces-Arab Contingent Forces to engage any country militarily.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> Many [[FIM-92 Stinger|Stinger missiles]] shipped to Pakistan for use by [[Afghan mujahideen]] were instead sold to Iran, which proved to be a defining factor for Iran in the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War#Attacks on shipping|Tanker war]].<ref name=\"Tauris\">{{cite book|last=Shah|first=Mehtab Ali|title=The Foreign Policy of Pakistan: Ethnic Impacts on Diplomacy, 1971\u20131994|year=1997|publisher=Tauris|location=London [u.a.]|isbn=1-86064-169-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7czT4fipTyoC&pg=PA30&dq=Zia+and+Iran&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=true}}</ref>\n\n===Soviet integration and Afghan civil war===\n{{Main|Soviet invasion of Afghanistan|War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)}}\n\nIn December 1979, the [[Soviet Union]] [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan|invaded]] fragile [[Socialist Afghanistan]] to protect its interests in Central Asia and as response to American dominance in the Middle East, in notably Israel, Iran, and many Arab states. In 1980, the Iraqi [[Iran\u2013Iraq War|attack]] on Iran, and subsequent Soviet [[Soviet support for Iraq during the Iran\u2013Iraq war|support]] for Iraq, improved Iranian ties with Pakistan.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Pakistan focused its covert support on the sectarian [[Afghan Pashtuns|Pashtun groups]] while Iran largely supported the [[Afghan Tajik|Tajik groups]], though they all fought as [[Afghan mujahideen]].<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />\n\nAfter the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, the rivalry between Iran and Pakistan intensified.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=The+Iran-Pakistan+rivalry+intensified+further+following+the+1989+Soviet+withdrawal+from+Afghanistan.+In+the+ensuing+civil+war,+the+Pakistani-backed+Taliban+fought+the+Iranian-supported+Northern+Alliance,+with+the+former+eventually+gaining+control+over+90+percent+of+Afghanistan.&source=bl&ots=LCjBpl4S4r&sig=tD2Gd-cwkpjrbRdWQ-a_YLakGos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT8MSzpqzRAhVBsJQKHfvQB2cQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=The%20Iran-Pakistan%20rivalry%20intensified%20further%20following%20the%201989%20Soviet%20withdrawal%20from%20Afghanistan.%20In%20the%20ensuing%20civil%20war%2C%20the%20Pakistani-backed%20Taliban%20fought%20the%20Iranian-supported%20Northern%20Alliance%2C%20with%20the%20former%20eventually%20gaining%20control%20over%2090%20percent%20of%20Afghanistan.&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=25|quote=The Iran-Pakistan rivalry intensified further following the 1989 Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan. In the ensuing civil war, the Pakistani-backed Taliban fought the Iranian-supported Northern Alliance, with the former eventually gaining control over 90 percent of Afghanistan.|via=}}</ref> After 1989, both state's policies in Afghanistan became even more divergent as Pakistan, under [[Benazir Bhutto]], explicitly supported [[Taliban]] forces in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Muhammad Hanif, IPRI\">{{cite web|last=Hanif|first=Muhammad|title=Pakistan-Iran relations: Future challenges|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:kZhdZjH9xdAJ:ipripak.org/articles/latest/pirf.pdf+pakistan+iran+relations&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjOBZ3pm8jDQIk9nLrqU6PHIuNjicvnhs46P35WTwUZI5iJqT_jvANMP6UtSIB-5YmWeoTpGmabFA4Ue67AuMoRBOgn9oEvc5QW_iBGmQhnn4fdgsPW5xixvV_p8xfXfb91Gzlk&sig=AHIEtbT2lXn8dBHWhB-WUnc57xFw4PaGew|work=Islamabad Policy Research Institute|publisher=Muhammad Hanif, IPRI|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> This resulted in a major breach, with Iran becoming closer to India.<ref name=\"Muhammad Hanif, IPRI\" /> Pakistan's support for the Sunni [[Taliban]] organization in Afghanistan became a problem for [[Shia]] Iran which opposed a Taliban-controlled Afghanistan.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Pakistani backed Taliban fought the Iranian backed Northern Alliance in Afghanistan and gained control of 90 percent of that country.<ref name=\":2\" /> As noted by a Pakistani foreign service officer, it was difficult to maintain good relations with Israel, Saudi Arabia, the United States, and Iran at the same time, given Iran's long history of rivalry with these states.<ref name=\"Muhammad Hanif, IPRI\" /> In 1995 Bhutto paid a lengthy state visit to Iran, which greatly relaxed relations. At a public meeting she spoke highly of Iran and Iranian society.<ref name=\"Benazir Bhutto in Iran (Press Release)\">{{cite web|last=Haq|first=Noor-ul-|title=Iran Pakistan relations|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:4vcUM_ZKq64J:ipripak.org/factfiles/ff88.pdf+pakistan+iran+relations&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShaMcs6udbKs5H5g6QA9GWNQ591WUTPRbbiitPq_7rrx0VDJH8iA8bk8t5ANogU8Er88kU4GJ2XF_1M6-Po1u59uWQ2-wNHd4IKXMFVmaQgZvqfy33-gS7Suy9jvMpDioeL734k&sig=AHIEtbQYPb2SCXgficETk0HK35okcLzZCQ|publisher=Benazir Bhutto in Iran (Press Release)|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> However, increasing activity by Shia militants in Pakistan strained relations further.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> This was followed by the Taliban's [[Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif 1997-1998|capture]] of the city of [[Mazar-i-Sharif]] in 1998, in which thousands of Shias were massacred, according to [[Amnesty International]].<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />  The most serious breach in relations came in 1998, after Iran accused [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|Taliban Afghanistan]] of taking [[1998 Iranian diplomats assassination in Afghanistan|11 Iranian diplomats, 35 Iranian truck drivers and an Iranian journalist]] hostage, and later killing them all.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Iran massed over 300,000 troops on the Afghan border and threatened to attack the Taliban government, which it had never recognized.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> This strained relations with Pakistan, as the Taliban were seen as Pakistan's key allies.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> In May 1998, Iran criticized Pakistan for its nuclear testing in the Chagai region, and held Pakistan accountable for global \"[[atomic proliferation]]\".<ref>See: [[Chagai-I]]</ref> New Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] acknowledged his country's nuclear capability on 7 September 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nti.org/e_research/profiles/Pakistan/Nuclear/chronology_2000.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108072216/http://www.nti.org/e_research/profiles/Pakistan/Nuclear/chronology_2000.html|title=NTI: Research Library: Country Profiles: Pakistan|archivedate=8 November 2010|work=NTI publications|accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Bilateral and Multilateral visits in the late 1990s===\n\nIn 1995, [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Benazir Bhutto]] paid a state visit to Iran to lay the groundwork for a memorandum on energy, and begin work on an [[Energy security]] agreement between the two countries. This was followed by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Nawaz Sharif]]'s visit to Tehran for the 8th OIC Summit Conference on 9\u201311 December 1997. While there Sharif held talks with [[President of Iran|President]] [[Mohammad Khatami|Khatami]], with a view to improving bilateral relations, as well as finding a solution to the Afghan crisis.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pakistan and the World (Chronology: October-December 1997)|journal=Pakistan Horizon|date=January 1998|volume=51|issue=1|pages=73\u201390|jstor=41394647|publisher=Pakistan Institute of International Affairs}}</ref>\n\nChief Executive General [[Pervez Musharraf]] paid a two-day visit to Tehran on 8\u20139 December 1999. This was his first visit to Iran (and third international trip) since his [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]] of 12 October 1999 and subsequent seizure of power in Pakistan. In Iran, Musharraf held talks with [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Mohammad Khatami]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistani military ruler meets Iran's Khatami|url=http://iranian.com/Times/1999/Decb/MahmoudAbad/news.html#93|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=The Iranian Times|date=9 December 1999|agency=Reuters}}</ref> and with the [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Iranian Supreme Leader]] [[Ali Khamenei]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran wants end to sectarian violence in Pakistan|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/1999/december/dec9d1999.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=9 December 1999|agency=Reuters}}</ref> This visit was arranged<ref>{{cite news|title=Musharraf leaves for Bahrain, Iran today, Pleads Pak-Iran joint efforts for Afghan peace|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/1999/december/dec8f1999.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=8 December 1999|agency=NNI}}</ref> to allow Musharraf to explain the reasons for his takeover in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saba|first=Sadeq|title=Musharraf on goodwill mission|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/554938.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=8 December 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe meetings included discussions on the situation in Afghanistan, which were intended to lead both countries to \"coordinate the policies of our two countries for encouraging the peace process through reconciliation and dialogue among the Afghan parties\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran & Pakistan to \"coordinate\" their policies towards Afghanistan|url=http://iranian.com/Times/1999/Decb/MahmoudAbad/news.html#94|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=The Iranian Times|date=9 December 1999|agency=AFP}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iran, Pakistan to \"coordinate\" their policies towards Afghanistan|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/1999/december/dec10g1999.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=9 December 1999|agency=AFP}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 Iran accused Pakistani troops of war crimes at [[Bamyan|Bamiyan]] in Afghanistan and claimed that Pakistani warplanes had, in support of the Taliban, bombarded Afghanistan's last Shia stronghold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-09-14/news/9809140197_1_shiite-taliban-sunni|title=Iran Raises Anti-pakistan Outcry|last=Schmetzer|first=Uli|date=14 September 1998|work=Chicago Tribune|quote=KARACHI, Pakistan \u2014 Iran, which has amassed 200,000 troops on the border with Afghanistan, accused Pakistan on Sunday of sending warplanes to strafe and bombard Afghanistan's last Shiite stronghold, which fell hours earlier to the Taliban, the Sunni militia now controlling the central Asian country.|access-date=5 January 2017|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1998/09/16/afghanistan-arena-for-a-new-rivalry/eeedba2f-03b7-4ed6-ba97-91e51e633e96/|title=Afghanistan: Arena For a New Rivalry|last=Constable|first=Pamela|date=16 September 1998|work=The Washington Post|quote=Taliban officials accused Iran of providing military support to the opposition forces; Tehran radio accused Pakistan of sending its air force to bomb the city in support of the Taliban's advance and said Iran was holding Pakistan responsible for what it termed war crimes at Bamiyan. Pakistan has denied that accusation and previous allegations of direct involvement in the Afghan conflict. Also fueling the volatile situation are ethnic and religious rivalries between the Taliban, who are Sunni Muslims of Afghanistan's dominant Pashtun ethnic group, and the opposition factions, many of which represent other ethnic groups or include Shiite Muslims. Iran, a Shiite Muslim state, has a strong interest in promoting that sect; Pakistan, one of the Taliban's few international allies, is about 80 percent Sunni.|access-date=5 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Relations since 2000==\n[[File:Pakistan Consul General met with the Mayor of Mashhad - Seyyed Sowlat Mortazavi and Qazi Habib ul-Rahman 5.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|Pakistan Consul General met with the Mayor of [[Mashhad]]]]\nSince 2000, relations between Iran and Pakistan have begun to normalize, and economic cooperation has strengthened. The [[9-11 terrorist attacks|9/11 terrorist attacks]] on the United States changed the foreign policy priorities of both Iran and Pakistan.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> The [[George W. Bush administration]]'s tough stance forced President Pervez Musharraf to support Washington's [[War on Terror]], which ended Taliban rule in Kabul. Though Iranian officials welcomed the move, they soon found themselves encircled by [[U.S. forces]] in Pakistan, Afghanistan, Central Asia, and the Persian Gulf.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />\n\nPresident Bush's inclusion of the [[Islamic Republic]] as part of an \"[[Axis of Evil]]\" also led some Iranian officials to presume that Tehran might be next in line for [[Covert United States foreign regime change actions|regime change]], ending whatever ''d\u00e9tente'' had occurred in [[Iran\u2013United States relations|Iran\u2013U.S.]] ties under Khatami.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Bush's emphasis on transformative diplomacy and democratization worried Iranian leaders further.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />\n\n===Bilateral visits after 2000===\nIn April 2001, the [[Supreme National Security Council|Secretary of Supreme National Security Council]] [[Hassan Rowhani]] (who is President of Iran since August 2013) paid a state visit to Pakistan and met with [[Pervez Musharraf]] and his cabinet.<ref name=\"Dawn News Archives\">{{cite news|last=Alvi|first=Ahmad Hasan|title=Chief Executive calls for stronger defence ties with Iran|url=http://www.lib.virginia.edu/area-studies/SouthAsia/SAserials/Dawn/2001/apr2801.html#chie|accessdate=19 December 2012|newspaper=Dawn News|date=28 April 2001}}</ref> During this visit, Iran and Pakistan agreed to put their differences aside and agree on a broad-based government for Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Dawn News Archives\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan, Iran to promote reconciliation in Afghanistan|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/2001/april/apr27d2001.html|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=27 April 2001|agency=Kyodo}}</ref>\n\nIranian Foreign Minister [[Kamal Kharazi]] paid a two-day visit to Islamabad from 29\u201330 November 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hussain|first=Talat|title=Pakistan, Iran seek to settle Afghan differences|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/asiapcf/south/11/29/gen.pakistan.iran/index.html|accessdate=31 August 2013|publisher=CNN|date=29 November 2001}}</ref> Kharazi met with Foreign Minister [[Abdul Sattar (diplomat)|Abdul Sattar]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Kharrazi links peace to broad-based govt|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2001/11/30/top3.htm|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=30 November 2001|author=M. Ziauddin|author2=Faraz Hashmi}}</ref> and President Musharraf.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan, Iran agree to lay gas pipeline: Trade ties being cemented|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2001/12/01/top1.htm|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=1 December 2001|author=Staff Reporter}}</ref> Iran and Pakistan vowed to improve their relations, and agreed to help establish a broad-based, multi-ethnic government under U.N. auspices.<ref>{{cite news|last=Iqbal|first=Nadeem|title=Pakistan, Iran Mend Fences over Afghanistan|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2001/12/politics-pakistan-iran-mend-fences-over-afghanistan/|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=IPS|date=6 December 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe President of Iran, Mohammad Khatami, paid a three-day state visit to Pakistan from 23\u201325 December 2002, the first visit by an Iranian [[head of government]] since 1992.<ref name=\"CNN, December 24, 2002\">{{cite news|last=APP |title=Weapons found during Khatami visit |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-12-24/world/pakistan.khatami_1_kashmir-dispute-kashmiris-on-both-sides-zafarullah-khan-jamali?_s=PM:asiapcf |publisher=CNN |accessdate=25 May 2012 |date=11 March 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227064341/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-12-24/world/pakistan.khatami_1_kashmir-dispute-kashmiris-on-both-sides-zafarullah-khan-jamali?_s=PM%3Aasiapcf |archivedate=27 February 2013 }}</ref> It was a high-level delegation, consisting of the Iranian cabinet, members of the [[Iranian parliament]], [[Vice President of Iran|Iranian Vice-President]] and President Khatami.<ref name=\"CNN, December 24, 2002\" /> This visit was meant to provide a new beginning to Iran\u2013Pakistan relations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Muir|first=Jim|title=Iran and Pakistan: A new beginning|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2601521.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=23 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Akhlaque|first=Qudssia|title=Khatami visit a turning point|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/23/top4.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=23 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zehra|first=Nasim|title=Khatami's visit may add a new dimension to Pakistan ties|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/226913|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Arab News|date=23 December 2002}}</ref> It would also allow for high-level discussions on the future of the [[Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline|Iran\u2013Pakistan\u2013India pipeline]] (IPI) project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Khatami visit to push South Asia pipeline project|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/south/12/23/pakistan.iran/|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=23 December 2002}}</ref> Khatami met, and had detailed discussions, with both President Musharraf<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran seeks to boost Pakistan ties|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2600439.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|publisher=BBC|date=24 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Economic ties top priority, says Khatami|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/24/top1.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=24 December 2002|agency=APP}}</ref> and the new Prime Minister [[Zafarullah Khan Jamali]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran and Pakistan boost ties|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2605309.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|publisher=BBC|date=25 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=ul Haque|first=Ihtasham|title=Resolution of Kashmir issue soon: Khatami|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/25/top1.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=DAWN|date=25 December 2002}}</ref> Several accords were signed between Iran and Pakistan in this visit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Four accords signed with Iran|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/25/nat12.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=25 December 2002|agency=APP}}</ref> Khatami also delivered a talk on \"Dialogue Among Civilizations,\" at [[The Institute of Strategic Studies]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iranian president lauds Iqbal's poetry|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/25/nat16.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=25 December 2002|agency=APP}}</ref> The presidential delegation initially visited Islamabad, and then followed that up with a visit to Lahore,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hanif|first=Intikhab|title=Khatami concerned at atrocities in Kashmir|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/27/nat27.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=27 December 2002}}</ref> where Khatami also paid his respects at the tomb of Allama Sir [[Muhammad Iqbal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Khatami calls for talks on Kashmir|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/226998|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Arab News|date=26 December 2002}}</ref> A Joint communique was issued by Iran and Pakistan on the conclusion of Khatami's visit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran calls for better strategic relations: Joint communique|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/27/top1.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=27 December 2002|author=Staff Reporter}}</ref> On his return to Tehran, Khatami evaluated the trip as \"positive and fruitful\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Khatami terms visit fruitful|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/27/nat47.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=27 December 2002|agency=PPI}}</ref>\n\nAs in return, Jamali paid a state visit in 2003 where he held talks with economic cooperation, security of the region, and better bilateral ties between Pakistan and Iran.<ref name=\"Daily Times, Wednesday, October 22, 2003\">{{cite web|title=Jamali talks trade with Khatami|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_22-10-2003_pg1_3|work=Daily Times|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>  During this visit, Jamali gave valuable advises to Iranian leadership on their [[Iranian nuclear programme|nuclear programme]] \"against the backdrop of the country's\" negotiations with the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA), and measures to strengthen economic relations between the two countries.<ref name=\"Daily Times, Thursday, October 16, 2003\">{{cite news|author=Shaukat Paracha |title=amali to discuss growing Indo-Iran ties with Khatami |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_16-10-2003_pg7_12 |accessdate=25 May 2012 |newspaper=Daily Times |date=16 October 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050518095538/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_16-10-2003_pg7_12 |archivedate=18 May 2005 }}</ref>\n\n===Military and security===\nIranian support for Pakistan dates back to the 1960s when Iran supplied Pakistan with American military weaponry and spare parts after America cut off their military aid to Pakistan.<ref name=Rubin>{{cite book|last=Rubin|first=Barry|title=Paved With Good Intentions|year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-502805-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/pavedwithgoodint00rubi/page/116 116]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/pavedwithgoodint00rubi/page/116}}</ref> After [[1971 Indo-Pakistani War]], new Prime minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] immediately withdrew Pakistan from [[Central Treaty Organization|CENTO]] and [[Southeast Asia Treaty Organization|SEATO]] after Bhutto thought that the military alliances failed to protect or appropriately assist Pakistan and instead alienated the [[Soviet Union]]. A serious military cooperation between took place during the [[Balochistan conflict|Balochistan insurgency]] phases against the [[Balochistan Liberation Army|armed separatist movement]] in 1974\u201377.<ref name=\"Greenwood Press\">{{cite book|last=Minaham|first=James|title=Encyclopedia of the stateless nations : ethnic and national groups around the world|year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport (Connecticut)|isbn=0-313-31617-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OLKKVXgEpkoC&pg=PA258&dq=pakistan+iran+military+relations&hl=en#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20iran%20military%20relations&f=true|accessdate=30 November 2012|page=google books|chapter=The Dravidians: Baloch}}</ref>  Around ~100,000 Pakistan and Iranian troops were involved in quelling the separatist organizations in Balochistan and successfully put the resistance down in 1978\u201380.<ref name=\"Greenwood Press\" /> In May 2014, the two countries agreed to joint operations against terrorists and drug traffickers in the border regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pakistan-Iran agree for joint Anti-Terrorist and Anti-Drug operations|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/pakistan-iran-agree-for-joint-anti-terrorist-and-anti-drug-operations/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, following a [[2019 Khash\u2013Zahedan suicide bombing|suicide bombing in Khash\u2013Zahedan]] which killed 27 [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] and wounded 13 others, Iranian officials criticised Pakistan. Iranian Major General [[Mohammad Ali Jafari]] asked Pakistan to conduct crack down against armed group Jaish al-Adl before Tehran takes it revenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/02/iran-warns-pakistan-crack-jaish-al-adl-190216071021469.html|title=Iran warns Pakistan to crack down on Jaish al-Adl|date=16 February 2019|work=Al Jazeera}}</ref> In February 2019, Bahram Ghasemi, speaking for the Foreign Ministry of Iran, said it would not tolerate what it saw as Pakistan's \"inability to stop cross-border attacks in Iran\".<ref name=\"Naya2019\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Either Confront Terrorist Groups Or Allow Iranian Forces To Enter\u2019: Iran Threatens Pakistan |url=https://www.nayadaur.tv/2019/02/either-confront-terrorist-groups-or-allow-iranian-forces-to-enter-iran-threatens-pakistan |website=Naya Daur |accessdate=20 February 2019 |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> Pakistan, in turn, offered Iran cooperation in investigating the bombing, and expressed sympathy for the victims of the attack. A Pakistani delegation was due to travel to Iran.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1464488 Pakistan offers cooperation to Iran over probe into attack], ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|The Dawn]]''.</ref>\n\n===Iran's view on Kashmir issue===\nOn 19 November 2010 Iran's [[Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah Ali Khamenei appealed to Muslims worldwide to back the freedom struggle in [[Jammu and Kashmir]], equating the dispute with the ongoing conflicts of the Greater Middle East region.\n\n\"Today the major duty of the elite of the Islamic Ummah is to provide help to the Palestinian nation and the besieged people of [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]], to sympathize and provide assistance to the nations of Afghanistan, Pakistan, Iraq and [[Occupied Kashmir]], to engage in struggle and resistance against the aggressions of the [[United States]], the [[Zionist Regime]]...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahazi-islami.com/news-events/index.asp?NewsID=257|title=Mahazi Islami - News & Events|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iran-times.com/khamenehi-says-kashmir-oppressed/|title=Khamenehi says Kashmir oppressed|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> He further said that Muslims should be united and \"spread awakening and a sense of responsibility and commitment among Muslim youth throughout Islamic communities\".<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/twice-in-7-days-iran-talks-of-oppressed-kashmir/articleshow/59454492.cms|title=Twice in seven day, Iran talk of oppressed Kashmiri|accessdate=5 July 2017|publisher=Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"India Today\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/irans-supreme-leader-khamenei-rakes-up-kashmir-bogey-twice-in-two-weeks-1022519-2017-07-05|title=Iran's supreme leader Khamenei rakes up Kashmir bogey twice in two weeks|accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"The wire\">{{cite news|url=https://thewire.in/diplomacy/iran-khamenei-kashmir|title=For the First Time in Seven Years, Ayatollah Khamenei Rakes Up Kashmir|accessdate=27 June 2017|publisher=The wire}}</ref><ref name=\"FirstPost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/irans-ayatollah-ali-khamenei-urges-muslims-in-kashmir-to-repudiate-oppressors-3747153.html|title=Iran's Ayatollah Ali Khamenei urges Muslims in Kashmir to 'repudiate oppressors'|accessdate=26 June 2017|publisher=FirstPost}}</ref>\n\nThe thrust of his speech was directed at Israel, India, and the US, but also made a veiled reference to Pakistan's nuclear program:\n\n\"The US and the West are no longer the unquestionable decision-makers of the Middle East that they were two decades ago. Contrary to the situation 20 years ago, nuclear know-how and other complex technologies are no longer considered inaccessible daydreams for Muslim nations of the region.\"\n\nHe said the US was bogged down in Afghanistan and \"is hated more than ever before in disaster-stricken Pakistan\".\n\nA former president of Iran (1981\u201389), Khamenei succeeded Ayatollah Khomeini as the spiritual head of the Iranian people. A staunch supporter of Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, Khamenei is believed to be highly influential in Iran's foreign policy.\n\nKhamenei visited [[Jammu and Kashmir]] in the early 1980s and delivered a sermon at Srinagar's Jama Masjid mosque.\n\nIn 2017, Iran's leader Ayatollah Khamenei said that [[Kashmiris]] are being oppressed. He also urged Muslim world to \"openly support people of [[Kashmir]] and repudiate oppressors and tyrants who attacked people in [[Ramadan]]\".<ref name=\"Times of India\"/><ref name=\"India Today\"/><ref name=\"The wire\"/><ref name=\"FirstPost\"/>\n\nBy 2019, after India had removed the autonomy of Indian Kashmir, Pakistan's Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]] thanked Iran's Supreme Leader, for his support of Pakistan's position on the Kashmir issue.<ref>https://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/513803-PM-Imran-thanks-Iranian-Supreme-Leader-for-supporting-Kashmir-issue-</ref>\n\n===Atoms for Peace cooperation===\n{{Further|Atoms for Peace}}\n\nSince 1987, Pakistan has steadily blocked any Iranian acquisition of [[nuclear weapons]]; however, Pakistan has wholeheartedly supported Iran's viewpoint on the issue of its [[Nuclear program of Iran|nuclear energy program]], maintaining that \"Iran has the right to develop its nuclear program within the ambit of NPT.\" In 1987 Pakistan and Iran signed an agreement on civil nuclear energy cooperation, with [[Zia-Ul-Haq]] personally visiting Iran as part of its \"Atoms for Peace\" program.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\">{{cite web|title=A.Q. Khan and onward proliferation from Pakistan|work=The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, Zia calculated that this cooperation with Iran was purely a \"civil matter\", necessary for maintaining good relations with Tehran.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\" /> According to IAEA, Iran wanted to purchase fuel-cycle technology from Pakistan, but was rebuffed.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\" /> Zia did not approve any further nuclear deals, but one of Pakistan's [[Abdul Qadeer Khan|senior scientists]] did secretly hand over a sensitive report on centrifuges in 1987\u201389.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\" />\n\nIn 2005, [[IAEA]] evidence showed that Pakistani cooperation with Iran's nuclear program was limited to \"non-military spheres\",<ref name=\"Columbia Univ Pr\" /> and was peaceful in nature.<ref name=\"Columbia Univ Pr\" /> Tehran had offered as much as $5 billion for nuclear weapons technology in 1990, but had been firmly rejected. Centrifuge technology was transferred in 1989; since then, there have been no further atoms for peace agreements.<ref name=\"Columbia Univ Pr\">{{cite book|last=Hussain|first=Zahid|title=Frontline Pakistan The Struggle With Militant Islam.|year=2008|publisher=Columbia Univ Pr|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=978-0-231-14225-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cD36RbtSKNkC&pg=PA166&dq=pakistan+iran+military+relations&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=true}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, IAEA evidence revealed that the centrifuge designs transferred in 1989 were based on early commercial power plant technology, and were riddled with technical errors; the designs were not evidence of an active nuclear weapons program.<ref>Linzer, Dafna (23 August 2005). \"No Proof Found of Iran Arms Program; Uranium Traced to Pakistani Equipment\". The Washington Post. Retrieved 20 September 2009.</ref>\n\n===Non-belligerent policy and official viewpoint===\nDifficulties have included disputes over trade, and political position. While Pakistan's [[Foreign policy of Pakistan|foreign policy]] maintains balanced relations with [[Pakistan\u2013Saudi Arabia relations|Saudi Arabia]], the [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations|United States]], and the [[Pakistan\u2013European Union relations|European Union]], Iran tends to warn against it, and raised concerns about Pakistan's absolute backing of the [[Taliban]] during the [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1996\u20132001)|fourth phase]] of [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|civil war]] in [[Afghanistan]] in the last years of the 20th century.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> \nThrough a progressive reconciliation and chaotic diplomacy, both countries come closer to each other in last few years. In the changing security environment, Pakistan and Iran boosted their ties by maintaining the warmth in the relationship without taking into account the pressures from international actors.<ref>http://www.opinion-maker.org/2012/03/pak-iran-relations-the-changing-scenario/</ref>\n\nOn Iran's nuclear program and its own relations with Iran, Pakistan adopted a policy of [[Neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]], and played a subsequent [[non-belligerent]] role in easing the tension in the region. Since 2006, Pakistan has been strategically advising Iran on multiple occasions to counter the international pressure on its nuclear program to subsequently work on civil nuclear power, instead of active nuclear weapons program.<ref name=\"Dawn News Archives, 2006\">{{cite news|title=2006: Shaukat Aziz told Ahmedinejad to abandon Iran\u2019s nuclear weapons program|url=http://dawn.com/2011/07/09/2006-shaukat-aziz-told-ahmedinejad-to-abandon-irans-nuclear-weapons-program/|accessdate=30 May 2012|newspaper=Dawn News|date=9 July 2011}}</ref> On international front, Pakistan has been a great advocate for Iranian usage of nuclear energy for economics and civil infrastructure while it steadily stop any Iranian acquisition of nuclear weapons, fearing another nuclear armed race with Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Geo Pakistan\">{{cite news|title=Pakistan supports peaceful use of Nuclear energy by Iran: PM Gilani|url=http://www.geo.tv/GeoDetail.aspx?ID=42475|accessdate=26 August 2012|newspaper=Geo Pakistan|date=1 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130419071118/http://www.geo.tv/GeoDetail.aspx?ID=42475|archivedate=19 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech at [[Harvard University]] in 2010, the Pakistan's [[Foreign Minister of Pakistan|foreign minister]] [[Shah Mehmood Qureshi]] justified Iran's nuclear program as peaceful and argued that Iran had \"no justification\" to pursue [[nuclear weapons]], citing the lack of any immediate threat to Iran, and urged Iran to \"embrace overtures\" from the United States. Qureshi also observed that Iran had signed the [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty]] and should respect the treaty.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran doesn't need nuclear weapons: Qureshi|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/64577/iran-doesnt-need-nuclear-weapons-qureshi/|accessdate=31 December 2011|newspaper=International Herald Tribune|date=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIran and Pakistan have been described as competitors for influence in the Middle East by some geo-political analysts, who argue a nuclear armed Iran could further agitate Pakistan.<ref>https://books.google.ca/books?id=hOyMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=iranian+influence+in+pakistan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFlbXDs97mAhVNbs0KHT40Clw4FBDoAQhuMAg#v=onepage&q=iranian%20influence%20in%20pakistan&f=false</ref>\n\nBoth countries also have a history of mutual distrust, accusing each other of supporting religious and ethnic rebels within each other's borders.<ref>https://www.dw.com/en/after-soleimani-killing-irans-proxy-war-to-impact-afghanistan-and-pakistan/a-51918670</ref>\n\n===Flood relief===\nDuring the [[2019 Iran floods]], Pakistan's [[National Disaster Management Authority (Pakistan)|National Disaster Management Authority]], on the order of country's Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]] sent 32 tonnes of relief goods to Iran. The consignment comprising two shipments contained 500 tents, 3,300 blankets and emergency medical kits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.mehrnews.com/news/143977/Pakistan-dispatches-humanitarian-assistance-to-flood-hit-Iran|title=Pakistan dispatches humanitarian assistance to flood hit Iran|date=10 April 2019|work=Mehr News Agency|access-date=7 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411153757/https://en.mehrnews.com/news/143977/Pakistan-dispatches-humanitarian-assistance-to-flood-hit-Iran|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1947574/1-pakistan-sends-humanitarian-aid-flood-hit-iran/|title=Pakistan sends humanitarian aid to flood-hit Iran|date=10 April 2019|work=Express Tribune}}</ref> The relief goods were transferred using two [[C-130]] aircraft. Previously Pakistan's Foreign Office (FO) spokesperson, Dr. Muhammad Faisal, condoled with the families of the victims. The spokesperson further claimed that Pakistan is ready to provide humanitarian assistance to Iran in rescue effort. He claimed that people of Pakistan stand in solidarity with Iranian people in their difficult time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/04/08/pakistan-expresses-grief-over-iran-floods/|title=Pakistan sends two C-130 aircrafts &#91;sic&#93; to Iran with flood relief goods|date=9 April 2019|work=Pakistan Today|access-date=7 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411163539/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/04/08/pakistan-expresses-grief-over-iran-floods/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Trade and Economics==\n[[File:Iran-Pakistan-India.JPG|thumb|right|Modified image of Iran-Pakistan national gas pipeline.]]\n\nRelations between Iran and Pakistan improved after the removal of the Taliban in 2002, but tensions remain. Pakistan has been under a strong influence of [[Saudi Arabia]] in its competition with Shiite majority Iran for influence across the broader Islamic world, which it already has in its allied nations Lebanon and Syria. Iran considers northern and western Afghanistan as its sphere of influence since its population is Persian [[Dari (Eastern Persian)|Dari]] speaking. Pakistan considers southern and eastern Afghanistan as its sphere of influence since it is Pashto and Baloch speaking such as the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and [[Baluchistan (Pakistan)|Baluchistan]], respectively.\n\n===Free Trade Agreement===\nIn 2005, Iran and Pakistan had conducted US$500 million of trade. The land border at [[Taftan (Balochistan)|Taftan]] is the conduit for trade in electricity and oil. Iran is extending its railway network towards [[Taftan (Balochistan)|Taftan]].\n\nThe [[Iran-Pakistan-India gas pipeline|Iran-Pakistan-India pipeline]] (IPI Pipeline) is currently under discussion; though India backed out from the project. The [[Indian government]] was under pressure by the [[United States]] against the [[Iran-Pakistan-India pipeline|IPI pipeline]] project, and appears to have heeded [[Foreign policy of the United States|American policy]] after India and the United States proceeded to sign the [[Indo-US civilian nuclear agreement|nuclear deal]]. In addition, the [[Sanctions on Iran|international sanctions]] on Iran due to its controversial [[Nuclear program of Iran|nuclear program]] could also become a factor in derailing [[Iran-Pakistan-India pipeline|IPI pipeline]] project altogether.\n\nTrade between the two countries has increased by \u00a31.4 billion in 2009.<ref name=\"The Nation, 2012\">{{cite news|last=Iranian Embassy|title=Pak-Iran economic relations|url=http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/columns/18-Feb-2012/pak-iran-economic-relations|accessdate=27 November 2012|newspaper=The Nation, 2012|date=18 February 2012}}</ref> In 2007-08, annual Pakistan merchandise trade with Iran consisted of $256 million in imports and $218.6 million in export, according to [[World Trade Organization|WTO]].<ref name=\"World Trade Organization\">{{cite web|last=WTO|title=Iran's Economic Partner|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:83mfoFym4XwJ:www.fpcci.com.pk/trade-with-countries/Iran.pdf+pakistan+iran+trade+statistics&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgtr_nqUg5eYfIv0Xp9ETk4yZn46-rXm20_1-qkg21VS7RLXOvvPLDcxQ-9zoD6un8Fo4qq5Qb5xIdM3HJpPiC2FSnH5OGsr8z6i0jUTm4sGIlD-H8gM0BhJ5BC20U_0ugw7xCO&sig=AHIEtbSZt8_AZDYrteEQ7wgNb2w2Hau1qA|publisher=World Trade Organization|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Bilateral trade===\nOn 12 January 2001, Pakistan and Iran formed a \"Pakistan-Iran Joint Business Council\" (PIJB) body on trade disputes.<ref name=\"Dawn Archives, 2001\">{{cite news|last=Reporter|title=Pakistan, Iran form body on trade disputes|url=http://www.lib.virginia.edu/area-studies/SouthAsia/SAserials/Dawn/2001/jan1301.html#iran|accessdate=19 December 2012|newspaper=Dawn Archives, 2001|date=13 January 2001}}</ref> The body works on to encourage the privatization in Pakistan and economic liberalization on both sides of the countries.<ref name=\"Dawn Archives, 2001\" /> In 2012, the bilateral trade exceeded $3 billion.<ref name=\"Daily Pakistan 2012\">{{cite news|last=Staff Report|title=Pakistan to consider barter trade with Iran|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C10%5C10%5Cstory_10-10-2012_pg5_5|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper=Daily Pakistan 2012|date=10 October 2012}}</ref> Official figures from the [[State Bank of Pakistan]] for fiscal year 2011-12 indicate imports of $124 million and exports of $131 million, which had collapsed to $36 million of exports to Iran and less than $1 million of imports for the year to April 2015. In 2011, the trade between Iran and Pakistan stood at less than $1 billion and the common geographical borders as well as religious affinities are among other factors, which give impetus to enhanced level of trade.<ref name=\"Daily Pakistan 2012\" /> According to the media reports, Iran is the second-largest market of [[Rice production in Pakistan|Basmati rice]] of Pakistan, ranking after Iraq.<ref name=\"Daily Pakistan July 29\">{{cite news|last=Staff Report|title=Pakistan to consider barter trade with Iran|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C07%5C29%5Cstory_29-7-2012_pg5_5|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper=Daily Pakistan 29 July|date=29 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Techno-Entrepreneurship===\nMomentum of improvement of economic and political relationships between Iran and Pakistan has created a wave of bilateral agreements between Iranian and Pakistan authorities. Techno-entrepreneurship is the highly trending topic of discussion in the global development and in ECO region (Pakistan-Iran-Turkey), a lot of joint projects have been executed since 2016. ScienceTech+ Center was the first joint techno-entrepreneurship center, which was established by the Pakistani and Iranian entrepreneurs in a joint agreement between CODE Entrepreneurship Consultants Ltd (Pakistan) and Ideparvaran MashreghQazal Ltd (Iran).<ref name=\" \u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u062c\u0634\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0622\u067e \u0633\u0627\u06cc\u0646\u0633 \u062a\u06a9 \u067e\u0644\u0627\u0633\">{{cite news|last=Reporter|title=\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u062c\u0634\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0622\u067e \u0633\u0627\u06cc\u0646\u0633 \u062a\u06a9 \u067e\u0644\u0627\u0633|url=http://www.iribnews.ir/fa/news/1670974/%D9%86%D8%B4%D8%B3%D8%AA-%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%B1%DB%8C-%D8%AC%D8%B4%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87-%DA%A9%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B1%DB%8C%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%A8%DB%8C%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%84%D9%84%DB%8C-%D8%B3%D8%A7%DB%8C%D9%86%D8%B3-%D8%AA%DA%A9-%D9%BE%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%B4%D9%87%D8%AF#iran|accessdate=22 Khordad 1396|newspaper= \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0635\u062f\u0627\u0648\u0633\u06cc\u0645\u0627, 2016|date=22 Khordad 1396}}</ref><ref name=\"ScienceTech+ Center\">{{cite web|last=Staff Report|title=Sciencetechplus International Accelerator|url=http://www.sciencetechplus.com|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> Several events under this platform are being organized by the [Pakistani in Iran] and Iranian authorities under the title of KarafarinShow in Iran, Pakistan and Turkey.<ref name=\"KarafarinShow\">{{cite web|last=KarafarinShow|title=KarafarinShow|url=https://www.karafarinshow.com|publisher=ScienceTech+|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Effects of US sanctions on Iran====\n{{Main|U.S. sanctions against Iran}}\n\nThe U.S. economic sanctions on Iran regarding their [[Iranian nuclear program|nuclear program]] generally affected Pakistan's industrial sector.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\">{{cite news|last=Our Correspondents|title=Pakistan loses Iran\u2019s mango market|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/395445/pakistan-loses-irans-mango-market/|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper=Tribune Express|date=5 January 2013}}</ref>  The fruit industry of Pakistan have reportedly lost a lucrative market in Iran, where at least 30,000 tons of [[mango]] were exported previously, as a result of the trade embargo imposed by the United States on Tehran.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\" /> According to the statistics by Pakistan, the fruit industry and the exporters could not export around $10 million worth of mango during the current season.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\" /> The [[Ministry of Commerce (Pakistan)|Ministry of Commerce (MoCom)]] has been in direct contact with the [[US Department of Agriculture]] to resolve the issue through diplomatic channels.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\" />\n\n==Energy==\n\n===Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline===\n{{Main|Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline|Energy Security}}\n\nDiscussions between the governments of [[Government of Iran|Iran]] and [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistan]] started in 1994 for the gas pipelines and energy security.<ref name=downstream1>{{cite news|url=http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=10718|title=IPI Implementation Nearing 'Final Stage' \u2013 Pakistani Official|work=Downstream Today|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=8 May 2008|accessdate=10 May 2008}}</ref> A preliminary agreement was signed in 1995 by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Benazir Bhutto]] and [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani]], in which, this agreement foresaw construction of a pipeline from [[South Pars / North Dome Gas-Condensate field|South\u2013North Pars gas field]] to [[Karachi]] in Pakistan. Later, Iran made a proposal to extend the pipeline from Pakistan into India. In February 1999, a preliminary agreement between Iran and India was signed.<ref name=chaudhary>{{cite web|url= http://www.american.edu/TED/iranpipeline.htm|title= Iran to India Natural Gas Pipeline: Implications for Conflict Resolution & Regionalism in India, Iran, and Pakistan|publisher= [[School of International Service]]|first=Shamila N.|last=Chaudhary|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nIran has the world's second largest gas reserves, after [[Russia]], but has been trying to develop its oil and gas resources for years, due to sanctions by the West. However, the project could not take off due to different political reasons, including the new gas discoveries in [[List of natural gas fields|Miano, Sawan and Zamzama]] gas fields of Pakistan. The Indian concerns on pipeline security and Iranian indecisiveness on different issues, especially prices. The Iran-Pakistan-India (denoted as IPI Pipeline) project was planned in 1995 and after almost 15 years India finally decided to quit the project in 2008 despite severe energy crises in that country.\n\nIn February 2007, India and Pakistan agreed to pay Iran [[United States Dollar|US$]]4.93 per million [[British thermal unit|BTUs]] (US$4.67/GJ) but some details relating to price adjustment remained open to further negotiation.<ref name=irandaily1>{{cite news|url=http://iran-daily.com/1386/2880/html/economy.htm#s238905|title=Peace Pipeline Contract Soon, Gas Flow by 2011|newspaper=Iran Daily|date=1 July 2007|accessdate=10 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506083012/http://iran-daily.com/1386/2880/html/economy.htm#s238905|archivedate=6 May 2008}}</ref> Since 2008, Pakistan began facing severe criticism from the United States over any kind of energy deal with Iran. Despite delaying for years the negotiations over the IPI gas pipeline project, Pakistan and Iran have finally signed the initial agreement in Tehran in 2009. The project, termed as the peace pipeline by officials from both the countries, was signed by President Zardari and President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad of Iran. In 2009, India withdrew from the project over pricing and security issues, and after signing another civilian nuclear deal with the [[United States]] in 2008.<ref name=reuters170310>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE62G12C20100317\n|title=Pakistan, Iran sign deal on natural gas pipeline|first=Zeeshan|last=Haider|date=17 March 2010|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=upi190310a>{{cite news|url= http://www.upi.com/Science_News/Resource-Wars/2010/03/19/Pakistan-gas-pipeline-is-Irans-lifeline/UPI-27741269029633/|title=Pakistan gas pipeline is Iran's lifeline|work=[[United Press International|UPI]]|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref> However, in March 2010 India called on Pakistan and Iran for trilateral talks to be held in May 2010 in [[Tehran]].<ref name=upi190310b>{{cite news|url= http://www.upi.com/Science_News/Resource-Wars/2010/03/19/New-Delhi-calls-for-IPI-talks/UPI-15881269006235/|title=New Delhi calls for IPI talks|work=[[United Press International|UPI]]|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the initial design of the project, the 2,700&nbsp;km long pipeline was to cover around 1,100&nbsp;km in Iran, 1,000&nbsp;km in Pakistan and around 600&nbsp;km in India, and the size of the pipeline was estimated to be 56 inches in diameter. However, as India withdrew from the project the size of the pipeline was reduced to 42 [[inches|inch]]. In April 2008, Iran expressed interest in the [[People's Republic of China]]'s participation in the project.<ref name=downstream3>{{cite news|url= http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=10460|title=Ahmadinehjad Would Welcome Chinese Role In Gas Pipeline|publisher=Downstream Today|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=28 April 2008|accessdate=10 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nSince as early as in 2005, China and Pakistan are already working on a proposal for laying a trans-Himalayan pipeline to carry Middle Eastern crude oil to western China.<ref name=\"dailytimes.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010/08/08/story_8-8-2010_pg5_10|title=DailyTimes - Your Right To Know|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> Beijing has been pursuing Tehran and Islamabad for its participation in the pipeline project and willing to sign a bilateral agreement with Iran. China and Pakistan are already working on a proposal for laying a trans-Himalayan pipeline to carry Middle Eastern crude oil to western China.<ref name=\"dailytimes.com.pk\" /> In August 2010, Iran invited [[Bangladesh]] to join the project.<ref name=fe150810>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/more.php?news_id=109098&date=2010-08-15|title=Iran invites Bangladesh to join cross-border gas grid|first=Humayan|last=Kabir|newspaper=[[Financial Express (Bangladesh)|The Financial Express]]|date=15 August 2010|accessdate=20 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Power Transmissions===\nTehran has provided [[Euros|\u20ac]]50 million for laying of 170[[kilometer|Km]] transmission line for the import of 1000MW of electricity from Iran in 2009. Pakistan is already importing 34MW of electricity daily from Iran. The imported electricity is much cheaper than the electricity produced by the Independent Power Producers (IPPs) because [[Ministry of Petroleum of Iran#Gasoline subsidies|Iran subsidises oil and gas]] which feed the power plants.<ref>[http://www.iran-daily.com/1388/3366/html/economy.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408063452/http://www.iran-daily.com/1388/3366/html/economy.htm|date=8 April 2009}}</ref> Iran has also offered to construct a motorway between Iran and Pakistan connecting the two countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\\08\\17\\story_17-8-2010_pg7_24|title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |publisher=Daily Times|date=17 August 2010|accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Diplomacy and role in mediation==\nSince Iran has no diplomatic relations with the [[United States]]; the Iranian interests section in the United States is represented by the Embassy of Pakistan Embassy in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. Iranian nuclear scientist, [[Shahram Amiri]], thought to have been abducted by [[CIA]] from [[Saudi Arabia]], took sanctuary in the [[Embassy of Pakistan in Washington, D.C.|Pakistan Embassy in Washington, D.C]]. The Iranian government claimed the United States has trumped up charges they were involved with the [[9/11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2010/07/201071353210347523.html |title=Iranian scientist surfaces in US \u2013 Americas|work=Al Jazeera|date=13 July 2010|accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomatic missions===\n\n====Iranian missions in Pakistan====\nIran's chief diplomatic mission to Pakistan is the Iranian Embassy in Islamabad. The embassy is further supported by many Consulates located throughout in Pakistan.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\">{{cite web|title=Iranian presence in Pakistan|url=http://www.iranembassy.pk/en/embassy-home/location.html|publisher=Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref>  The Iranian government supports Consulates in several major Pakistan's cities including: [[Karachi]]<sup>\u2021</sup>, [[Lahore]]<sup>\u2021</sup>, [[Quetta]]<sup>\u2021</sup>, [[Peshawar]]<sup>\u2021</sup>.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" /> Iranian government maintains a cultural consulate-general,  Persian Research Center, and ''Sada-o-Sima'' center, all in Islamabad.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" /> Other political offices includes cultural centers in [[Lahore]]<sup>\u2020</sup>, Karachi<sup>\u2020</sup>, [[Rawalpindi]]<sup>\u2020</sup>, Peshawar<sup>\u2020</sup>, Quetta<sup>\u2020</sup>, [[Hyderabad, Pakistan|Hyderabad]]<sup>\u2020</sup>, and [[Multan]]<sup>\u2020</sup>.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" />\n* \u2021 ''denotes mission is [[Consulate General]]''\n* \u2020 ''denotes mission is ''Khana-e-Farhang'' (lit. culture center)''\n\nThere is also an [[Iran Air]] corporate office located in [[Karachi Metropolitan Corporation]] site.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" />\n\n===Immigration===\n{{Main|Iranians in Pakistan|Pakistanis in Iran|Pakistan Technical Assistance Programme}}\n\nIn the [[Balochistan (region)|Balochistan region]] of southeastern Iran and western Pakistan, the [[Balochi people]] routinely travel the area with little regard for the official border, causing considerable problems for the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps|Iranian Guards Corps]] and the [[Frontier Corps]] of [[Pakistan]]. Both countries have ongoing conflicts with [[Balochistan conflict|Balochi separatist]] groups.\n\nSince 2010, there has been an increase in meetings between senior figures of both governments as they attempt to find a regional solution to the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghan war]] and continue discussions on a proposed [[Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline]] and an [[Economic Cooperation Organization]].<ref name=\"Pakistan Today\">{{cite news|last=Staff reporter|first=w|title=Container Train line|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2011/12/economic-cooperation-organisation-insists-upon-container-train-reactivation|accessdate=26 October 2013|newspaper=Pakistan Today|date=12 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIranian media delegations have been visiting Pakistan annually since 2004, with many journalists settling in Pakistan. These visits have played an effective role in promoting mutual understanding and projecting a positive image of Pakistan in Iran.<ref name=\"Pakistan Embassy, Tehran\">{{cite web|last=. Khalid Aziz Babar, Ambassador of Pakistan to Tehran|title=Cultural relations of Pakistan and Iran|url=http://www.mofa.gov.pk/iran/contents.aspx?type=statements&id=2|publisher=Pakistan Embassy, Tehran|accessdate=26 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nNotable Pakistani political figures [[Benazir Bhutto|Benazir]], [[Murtaza Bhutto|Murtaza]], and [[Shahnawaz Bhutto]] were half [[Iranian Kurds]] on their [[Nusrat Bhutto|mother's side]].\n\n====Pakistani missions in Iran====\nPakistan's chief diplomatic mission to Iran is the Pakistani embassy in Tehran. It is further supported by two consulates-general located throughout Iran.<ref name=\"Embassy of Pakistan Presence\">{{cite web|title=Embassy of Pakistan in Iran|url=http://www.mofa.gov.pk/iran/contents.aspx?type=statements&id=2|publisher=Embassy of Pakistan Presence|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> The [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistani government]] supports its [[Consul (representative)|consulates]] in [[Mashhad]] and [[Zahedan|Zahidan]].<ref name=\"Embassy of Pakistan Presence\" />\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Pakistan International School and College Tehran|Pakistan International School and College - Tehran]] aims to serve and accommodate additional educational needs for Pakistani families living in Tehran.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iran|Pakistan}}\n* [[Iran-Pakistan border]]\n* [[Nuclear program of Iran]]\n* [[Iran-Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n* [[Persian language in South Asia]]\n* [[Pakistani Armed Forces#Middle Eastern Countries|Pakistan Armed Forces\u2014 Iranian Contingent]]\n* [[List of statistically superlative countries]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Relations of Iran and Pakistan}}\n* [http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/HA13Df03.html Asia Times on Iran-Pakistan relations]\n* Schoresch Davoodi & Adama Sow: ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20080216052138/http://www.aspr.ac.at/epu/research/rp_0807.pdf The Political Crisis of Pakistan in 2007]'' \u2013 [[European University Center for Peace Studies|EPU]] Research Papers: Issue 08/07, Stadtschlaining 2007 \u2013 Research Paper which also describes the relations between Pakistan and Iran\n* [http://www.dawn.com/2009/01/01/top6.html Pakistan, Iran to boost cooperation in power sector]\n*  Pattanayak, Dr. Satyanarayan : ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20131030071936/http://www.vijbooks.com/book/164/Dr-Satyanarayan-Pattanayak/Iran-s-Relations-with-Pakistan-A-Strategic-Analysis/9789380177656.html Iran's Relations with Pakistan: A Strategic Analysis]'' \u2013 [[United Services Institution of India|USI]] Research Book, May 2012 \u2013 A well researched book focuses on various facets of the Iran Pakistan relationship in a long term perspective by analyzing them under various Phases.\n\n{{Iran\u2013Pakistan relations}}\n{{Foreign relations of Iran}}\n{{Foreign relations of Pakistan}}\n\n <!-- fixcategory -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iran-Pakistan Relations}}\n[[Category:1947 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013Pakistan relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Iran|Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Islamic Republic of Pakistan}}\n{{cleanup|reason=Poor writing.|date=December 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox bilateral relations|Iran\u2013Pakistan|Iran|Pakistan|map=Iran Pakistan Locator.png}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n\nAfter [[Pakistan]] [[Partition of India|gained its independence]] in August 1947, [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iran]] was one of the first countries to [[Diplomatic recognition|recognize]] its sovereign status.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Pakistan's relations with Iran became strained at times due to sectarian tensions, as Pakistani [[Shia Islam|Shi'a]] [[Muslims]] claimed that they were being [[Shia\u2013Sunni relations|discriminated]] against under the [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]-biased [[Zia ul-Haq's Islamization|Islamization]] program being imposed throughout Pakistan by the [[military dictatorship]] [[Government of Pakistan|government]] of [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wLtA_J3VUt4C&pg=PA144&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIGTAA#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran's Foreign Policy in the Post-Soviet Era: Resisting the New International Order|last=Hunter|first=Shireen|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2010|isbn=9780313381942|location=|pages=144|quote=Since then, Pakistan's sectarian tensions have been a major irritant in Iranian-Pakistan relations.|via=}}</ref> [[Iran]] and [[Saudi Arabia]] (considered the \"leading authority\" of Shi'a and Sunni Muslims, respectively) used Pakistan as a battleground for [[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict|their proxy sectarian war]], and Pakistan's support for the [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi]] [[Taliban]] organization in Afghanistan [[Afghan Civil War (1992\u20131996)|by the 1990s]] became a problem for Shi'a Iran, which opposed a [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|Taliban-controlled Afghanistan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ceg-kSmft94C&pg=PA159&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Explaining Pakistan\u2019s Foreign Policy: Escaping India|last=Pande|first=Aparna|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2011|isbn=9781136818943|location=|pages=159|quote=Both Saudi Arabia and Iran used Pakistan as a battleground for their proxy war for the 'hearts and minds' of Pakistani Wahhabis and Non muslims with the resultant rise in sectarian tensions in Pakistan. The rise of the Taliban in Afghanistan in the 1990s further strained Pakistan-Iran relations. Pakistan's support of the Wahhabi Pashtun organization created problems for Shia Iran for whom a Taliban-controlled Afghanistan was a nightmare.|via=}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, both countries continue to cooperate economically [[Sanctions against Iran|where possible]] and are forming alliances in a number of areas of mutual interest, such as fighting the [[Illegal drug trade|drug trade]] along their border and combating the [[Insurgency in Balochistan|insurgency in the Balochistan region]]. Iran has also expressed an interest in joining the [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor|China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC)]].<ref>http://www.dawn.com/news/1285404</ref><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Iran-keen-to-become-part-of-China-Pak-Economic-Corridor/articleshow/54462795.cms</ref>\n\nPakistan is one of the only countries where Iran is viewed positively as per the polls conducted by [[Pew Research Center]]. Polls have consistently shown that a very high proportion of Pakistanis view their western neighbor positively.<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|last=Max Fisher|title=Iran is popular in Pakistan, overwhelmingly disliked everywhere else|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/01/11/iran-is-popular-in-pakistan-overwhelmingly-disliked-everywhere-else/|accessdate=19 March 2013|newspaper=Washington Post|date=11 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2015/06/18/irans-global-image-mostly-negative/|title=Iran\u2019s Global Image Mostly Negative|last=Zainulbhai|first=Hani|last2=Wike|first2=Richard|date=18 June 2015|website=PEW Research Center|publisher=|access-date=5 January 2017|quote=Even in Pakistan, opinion of Iran has somewhat soured, with negative ratings increasing from 8% to 16% over the past year.}}</ref> [[Supreme Leader of Iran]] [[Ali Khamenei|Ayatollah Khamenei]] has also called for the [[Pan-Islamism|sympathy and assistance]] of many [[Muslim world|Muslim nations]], including Pakistan.<ref>http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/as-modi-embraces-israel-irans-ayatollah-khamenei-urges-support-for-oppressed-muslims-of-kashmir/articleshow/59455486.cms</ref>\n\n== Country comparison ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n\n! Common Name !! [[Pakistan]] !! [[Iran]]\n\n|-\n! Official Name !! Islamic Republic of Pakistan !! Islamic Republic of Iran\n\n|-\n| Coat of Arms\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:State emblem of Pakistan.svg|130px]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:Emblem of Iran.svg|130px]]\n\n|-\n| Flag\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Pakistan|size=130px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Iran|size=130px|text=none}}\n\n|-\n| [[List of countries and dependencies by area|Area]]\n| 881,913&nbsp;km\u00b2 (340,509 sq mi)\n| 1,648,195&nbsp;km\u00b2 (636,372 sq mi)\n\n|-\n| [[List of countries by population|Population]]\n| 212,286,286<ref name=census>{{cite web |url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk |title=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/content/provisional-summary-results-5th-population-and-housing-census-2017-0 |website=pbscensus.gov.pk |access-date=2 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015113737/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/ |archive-date=15 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 82,531,700\n\n|-\n| [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density|Population Density]]\n| 244.4/km\u00b2 (633/sq mi)\n| 48/km\u00b2 (124.3/sq mi)\n\n|-\n| [[List of national capitals|Capital]]\n\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| [[Tehran]]\n|-\n| Largest Metropolitan Area\n| [[Karachi]] (16,051,521)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2017-08-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| [[Tehran]] (23,000,000)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913144137/http://citypopulation.de/world/Agglomerations.html|title=Major Agglomerations of the World - Population Statistics and Maps|date=2018-09-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| Government\n| [[Federalism|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|Parliamentary]] [[Republic]]\n|[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Presidential system|Presidential]] [[Republic]]\n\n|-\n| Current Leader\n| [[Imran Khan]]\n| [[Ali Khamenei]]\n|-\n|Official Languages\n| [[Urdu]]\n|[[Persian language|Farsi (Persian)]]\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP|GDP (nominal)]]\n| $284.21 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=68&pr.y=12&sy=2017&ey=2024&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=564&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC,PCPIPCH&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| $463.08 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=43&pr.y=15&sy=2017&ey=2021&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=429&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|GDP (PPP)]]\n| $1.202 Trillion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=75&pr.y=3&sy=2017&ey=2024&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=564&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| $1.471 Trillion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=43&pr.y=15&sy=2017&ey=2021&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=429&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP,NGDPDPC,PPPPC&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|GDP (nominal) per Capita]]\n| $1,388\n| $5,820\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP (PPP) per Capita]]\n| $5,872\n| $18,504\n|-\n| [[List of countries by Human Development Index|Human Development Index]]\n| {{increase}} 0.560 (<span style=\"color:#fc0;\">Medium</span>)\n| {{increase}} 0.798 (<span style=\"color:#fc0;\">High</span>)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by military expenditures|Military Expenditures]]\n| $11.4 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalfirepower.com/country-military-strength-detail.asp?country_id=pakistan|title=2020 Pakistan Military Strength|website=www.globalfirepower.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| $19.6 Billion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalfirepower.com/country-military-strength-detail.asp?country_id=iran|title=2020 Iran Military Strength|website=www.globalfirepower.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Antiquity ==\n{{Main|Achaemenid conquest of the Indus Valley|Persianate society|Indo-Persian culture}}\n[[File:Tribute in the Achaemenid Empire.jpg|thumb|Map showing the distribution of Achaemenid tax revenues, according to the [[Greeks|Greek]] historian [[Herodotus]]]]\nThe regions that comprise modern-day [[Iran]] and [[Pakistan]] have been under the rule of contiguous [[Eurasia|Eurasian]] polities at various points in history, as Pakistan straddles an intermediary zone between the [[Iranian Plateau]] and [[Indian subcontinent]]. The Persian [[Achaemenid Empire]], which spanned the area between the [[Balkans]] and the [[Indus River]] at its height, conquered the regions comprising of [[Balochistan|Baluchistan]], [[Sindh]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and [[Punjab, Pakistan|western Punjab]] during the reign of [[Darius the Great|Darius I]]. \n\n==Relations during the Cold War==\n{{Main|Cold War (1947\u201353)|Cold War (1953\u201362)}}\n\n[[Pahlavi dynasty|Imperial Iran]] maintained close relations with [[Pakistan]] during much of the [[Cold War]], owing to their mutual alliance with the [[United States]]-led [[Western Bloc]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=24\u201325|quote=Iran's relations with Pakistan and India in the mid-20th century were the mirror image of that which exists today. Whereas Tehran now sees New Delhi as a natural partner, it maintained much closer ties with Islamabad throughout most of the Cold War.|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\">{{cite web|last=Officials|title=Pak-Iran Relations Since Islamic Revolution: Genisis of Cooperation and Competition|url=http://www.iranembassy.pk/en/political-section/592-pak-iran-relations-since-islamic-revolution-genisis-of-cooperatio-and-competition.html|publisher=Embassy of Iran, Islamabad|accessdate=25 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410121859/http://www.iranembassy.pk/en/political-section/592-pak-iran-relations-since-islamic-revolution-genisis-of-cooperatio-and-competition.html|archivedate=10 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Iran was the first country to recognise Pakistan as an independent state, and the [[List of monarchs of Persia|Shah of Iran]] was the first head of any state to come on an official [[state visit]] to Pakistan (in March 1950).<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Since 1947, [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]], the [[Quaid-i-Azam|founder of Pakistan]], had successfully advocated a policy of fostering cordial relations with Iran in particular and the [[Muslim world]] in general.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Despite [[Shia\u2013Sunni relations|Shi'a-Sunni divisions]], desires for a [[Pan-Islamism|pan-Islamic identity]] became an important factor in shaping Iranian\u2013Pakistani relations, especially after the [[Iranian Revolution|1979 Islamic Revolution in Iran]].\n\n[[File:Fpbutto.jpg|thumb|200px|left|[[President of Pakistan|Pakistani President]] [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] meeting with [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iranian Queen]] [[Farah Pahlavi]], 1972]]\n\nIn May 1950, a treaty of friendship was signed by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Liaquat Ali Khan]] and the Shah of Iran. Some of the clauses of the treaty of friendship had wider geopolitical significance.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\">{{cite web|last=Pant|first=Harsh V.|title=Pakistan and Iran's Dysfunctional Relationship|url=http://www.meforum.org/2119/pakistan-and-irans-dysfunctional-relationship|work=Middle East Quarterly|accessdate=28 November 2012|date=Spring 2009}}</ref> Pakistan found a natural partner in Iran after the [[Government of India|Indian government]] chose to support [[President of Egypt|Egyptian President]] [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]], who was seeking to export a [[Pan-Arabism|pan-Arab ideology]] that threatened many of the more traditional Arab monarchies, a number of which were allied with the Shah.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Harsh V. Pant, a foreign policy writer, noted that Iran was a natural ally and model for Pakistan for other reasons as well. Both countries granted each other [[Most favoured nation|MFN]] status for trade purposes; the Shah offered Iranian oil and gas to Pakistan on generous terms, and the [[Imperial Iranian Armed Forces|Iranian]] and [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani militaries]] extensively cooperated to suppress the [[Insurgency in Balochistan|rebel movement in Baluchistan]].<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> During the [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Shah]]'s era, Iran moved closer to Pakistan in many fields.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Pakistan, Iran, and Turkey joined the United States-sponsored [[Baghdad Pact|Central Treaty Organization]], which extended a defensive alliance along the [[Soviet Union|Soviet Union's]] southern perimeter.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Iran played an important role in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]], providing Pakistan with nurses, medical supplies, and a gift of 5,000 tons of petroleum. Iran also indicated that it was considering an embargo on oil supplies to [[India]] for the duration of the armed conflict.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The Indian government believed that Iran had blatantly favored Pakistan.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> After the suspension of American military aid to Pakistan, Iran was reported to have purchased ninety [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabrejet]] fighter planes from [[West Germany]], and subsequently delivered them to Pakistan.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\nAlthough Pakistan's decision to join the Central Treaty Organization (CENTO) in 1955 was largely motivated by its [[Indo-Pakistani wars and conflicts|security imperatives regarding India]], Pakistan did not sign on until Iran was satisfied that the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] was not going to obstruct the nationalization of British oil companies in Iran.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> According to Dr. Mujtaba Razvi, Pakistan likely would not have joined CENTO had Iran been negatively affected during these events.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\nIran had again played a vital role for Pakistan in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]], this time supplying military equipment as well as diplomatic support against India. The Shah described the Indian attack as aggression and interference in [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Pakistan's domestic affairs]];<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> in an interview with a Parisian newspaper he openly acknowledged that \"We are one hundred percent behind Pakistan\".<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> [[Prime Minister of Iran|Iranian Prime Minister]] [[Amir-Abbas Hoveida]] followed suit, saying that \"Pakistan has been subjected to violence and force.\"<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> The Iranian leadership repeatedly expressed its opposition to the dismemberment of Pakistan, fearing it would adversely affect the domestic stability and security of Iran<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> by encouraging [[Kurdish separatism in Iran|Kurdish]] and [[Baloch nationalism|Baloch separatists]] to rise up against the Iranian government.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> In the same vein, Iran attempted to justify its supplying arms to Pakistan on the grounds that, in its desperation, Pakistan might fall into the lap of the Chinese.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> On the other hand, Iran changed its foreign priorities after making a move to maintain good relations with India.\n\nThe subsequent breakup of Pakistan in December 1971 convinced Iran that extraordinary effort was needed to protect the stability and territorial integrity of its eastern flank. With the emergence of [[Bangladesh]] as a separate state, the \"[[Two-nation theory (Pakistan)|Two-Nation Theory]]/[[Pakistan Movement]]\" received a severe blow and questions arose in the Iranian establishment as to whether the residual western part of Pakistan could hold together and remain a single country.<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\">{{cite journal|last=Alam|first=Shah|title=Iran\u2013Pakistan Relations: Political and Strategic Dimensions|journal=Strategic Analysis|date=20 December 2004|volume=28|issue=4|pages=20|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:tQHaWA6pkXgJ:www.idsa.in/system/files/strategicanalysis_salam_1204.pdf+Iran+pakistan+relations+1970s&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgpvNr5msxhiEG93UEzp5nCtujak6TcZZva0ITbwY1sSSy2AnSKDtEDgI32eOz_6bX_veJ06nb6ewBMEQ_iynP0g8LM3mldXkK7agUZcotXgvseoatRnlYsiR1U_26SctfIZ1SN&sig=AHIEtbTCi4g0Ksw-WOFlhcwrichNsu_cpA|accessdate=26 November 2012|publisher=\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses|language=English|format=google docs.|doi=10.1080/09700160408450157}}</ref> Events of this period caused significant perceptional changes in Tehran regarding Pakistan.\n\nWhen widespread [[1970s Operation in Balochistan|armed insurgency]] broke out in Pakistan's [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan province]] in 1973, Iran, fearing the insurgency might spill over into its own [[Sistan and Baluchestan Province|Sistan and Baluchistan Province]], offered large-scale support.<ref>[[Foreign Policy Centre]], \"On the Margins of History\", (2008), p.35</ref> The Iranians provided Pakistan with military hardware (including thirty [[Bell AH-1 Cobra|AH-1 Cobra]] attack helicopters), intelligence, and $200 million in aid.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4182151.stm|title=Pakistan risks new battlefront|accessdate=8 April 2006|date=17 January 2005|work=BBC News}}</ref> The government of then-[[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] declared its belief that, as in the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|1971 Bangladesh Liberation War]], India was once again behind the unrest and uprising of rebels in the Balochistan region. However, the Indian government denied any involvement, and claimed that it was fearful of further [[Balkanization|balkanisation]] of the [[Indian subcontinent|subcontinent]].<ref name=\"BBC News\" /> After three years of fighting the uprising was majorly suppressed.<ref name=\"BBC News\" />\n[[File:Mohammad Ali Jenah Iran stamp.jpg|right|thumb|1976 Iranian postage stamp featuring Pakistan's founder, [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah|Muhammed Ali Jinnah]]]]\n\nIn addition to military aid, the Shah of Iran offered considerable developmental aid to Pakistan, including oil and gas on preferential terms.<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\" /> Pakistan was a [[developing country]] and [[Power (international relations)|small power]], while Iran, in the 1960-70s, had the world's fifth largest military and a strong industrial base, and was the clear, undisputed regional superpower.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\">{{cite web |title=1971 war and Iran|url=http://iranembassy.pk/en/political-section/591-pak-iran-relation-since-1947.html|publisher=1971 war and Iran|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/panorama/hi/front_page/newsid_8084000/8084871.stm|title=BBC - Panorama - Iran Archives: Oil Barrels and the Gun|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> However, Iran's total dependence on the United States at that time for its economic development and military build-up had won it [[Arab League\u2013Iran relations|hostility]] from the [[Arab world]].<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> Tensions arose in 1974, when [[Pahlavi dynasty|Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] refused to attend the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|Islamic Conference]] in [[Lahore]] because [[History of Libya under Muammar Gaddafi|Libyan]] leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] had been invited to it, despite the known hostility between Libya and Iran.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" /> In 1976, Iran again played a vital and influential role by facilitating a rapprochement between Pakistan and [[Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\nIran's reaction to India's surprise 1974 [[Nuclear weapons testing|nuclear test]] detonation (codenamed ''[[Smiling Buddha]]'') was muted.<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\" /> During a state visit to Iran in 1977, Bhutto tried to persuade Pahlavi to support Pakistan's own clandestine [[Pakistan and weapons of mass destruction|atomic bomb project]].<ref name=\"\u00a9 The Institute for Defence Studies and Analyses\" /> Although the Shah's response is not known, there are indications that he refused to oblige Bhutto.<ref name=\"1971 war and Iran\" />\n\nIn July 1977, following political agitation by an opposition alliance, Bhutto was forced out of office in a [[1977 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The new [[Zia regime|military dictatorship government]], under [[General officer|General]] [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]], was ideologically [[Political Islam|ultraconservative]] and religiously oriented ([[Sunni Islam|Sunni-biased]]) in its nature and approach in contrast to the more secular Iran at the time.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\n===Relationship after the 1979 Iranian revolution===\n\nThe 1979 [[Iranian Revolution]] transformed Pakistan and Iran into rivals instead of partners.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=24|quote=The 1979 Iranian Revolution greatly altered the nature of Iran-Pakistan relations, transforming the two countries into rivals rather than partners.|via=}}</ref> Bhutto's ouster was followed a half year later by the [[Iranian Revolution]] and overthrow of the [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Shah of Iran]]. Iran's new Supreme Leader, the [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], withdrew the country from CENTO and ended its association with the United States.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The religiously influenced military government of Zia-ul-Haq and the Islamic Revolution in Iran suited one another well, and as such there was no diplomatic and political cleavage between them.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> In 1979, Pakistan was one of the first countries in the world to recognize the revolutionary regime in Iran. Responding swiftly to this revolutionary change, [[Foreign Minister of Pakistan]] [[Agha Shahi]] immediately undertook a state visit to Tehran, meeting with his Iranian [[Foreign Minister of Iran|counterpart]] [[Karim Sanjabi]] on 10 March 1979.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Both expressed confidence that Iran and Pakistan were going to march together to a brighter future.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> The next day, Agha Shahi held talks with the [[Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini]], in which developments in the region were discussed.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> On 11 April 1979, Zia famously declared that \"Khomeini is a symbol of Islamic insurgence\".<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> Reciprocating President Zia's sentiments, Imam Khomeini, in his letter, called for Muslim unity.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> He declared: \"Ties with Pakistan are based on Islam.\"<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" /> By 1981, however, Pakistan, under [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]], had once again formed close ties with the United States, a position it has remained in since.<ref name=\"Embassy of Iran, Islamabad\" />\n\n====Iranian influence on Pakistan's Shia population====\nIranian leaders had sought to extend their sphere of influence in Pakistan and to counter Saudi influence. As such, a pro-Iranian stance amongst many politicized Pakistani Shias is widespread. Many Pakistani Shia websites are filled with writings advocating the Khamanei regime.<ref>https://books.google.ca/books?id=t6aKCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA312&dq=pro-iranian+shias+in+pakistan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJu4r0z97mAhV0dc0KHds4A-YQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=pro-iranian%20shias%20in%20pakistan&f=false</ref>\n\n===Pakistani support for Iran during the Iran\u2013Iraq war===\n{{Main|Iran\u2013Iraq War|Pakistan and the Iran\u2013Iraq War}}\nWhile Pakistan remained neutral during the Iran-Iraq War, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's attempts to export the Iranian revolution fueled tensions between Pakistan's Sunnis and Shias.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=iran+pakistan+relations+shia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifquCKlqrRAhXEHJQKHYtiAaMQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=iran%20pakistan%20relations%20shia&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=24|quote=While Pakistan remained neutral during the Iran-Iraq War, which threatened the fledgling Islamic Republic's existence, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's efforts to export the Iranian Revolution fueled tensions in Pakistan between its Sunni majority and sizable Shia minority.|via=}}</ref> The militancy of Shia inspired by revolutionary Iran left many Pakistani Sunni feeling deeply threatened.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> President Zia, despite his pro-Saudi and anti-Shia sentiments,<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> had to manage his country's security carefully, knowing that Pakistan risked being dragged into a war with its closest neighbor because of its alliance with the United States.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> In support of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]], formed in 1981, around 40,000 personnel of the Pakistan Armed Forces were stationed in [[Saudi Arabia]] to reinforce the internal and external security of the region.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> Although high-ranking members of Pakistan Armed Forces strongly objected to the killing of Shia pilgrims in the [[1987 Mecca incident]] in Saudi Arabia, Zia did not issue any orders to Pakistan Armed Forces-Arab Contingent Forces to engage any country militarily.<ref name=\"Tauris\" /> Many [[FIM-92 Stinger|Stinger missiles]] shipped to Pakistan for use by [[Afghan mujahideen]] were instead sold to Iran, which proved to be a defining factor for Iran in the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War#Attacks on shipping|Tanker war]].<ref name=\"Tauris\">{{cite book|last=Shah|first=Mehtab Ali|title=The Foreign Policy of Pakistan: Ethnic Impacts on Diplomacy, 1971\u20131994|year=1997|publisher=Tauris|location=London [u.a.]|isbn=1-86064-169-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7czT4fipTyoC&pg=PA30&dq=Zia+and+Iran&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=true}}</ref>\n\n===Soviet integration and Afghan civil war===\n{{Main|Soviet invasion of Afghanistan|War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)}}\n\nIn December 1979, the [[Soviet Union]] [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan|invaded]] fragile [[Socialist Afghanistan]] to protect its interests in Central Asia and as response to American dominance in the Middle East, in notably Israel, Iran, and many Arab states. In 1980, the Iraqi [[Iran\u2013Iraq War|attack]] on Iran, and subsequent Soviet [[Soviet support for Iraq during the Iran\u2013Iraq war|support]] for Iraq, improved Iranian ties with Pakistan.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Pakistan focused its covert support on the sectarian [[Afghan Pashtuns|Pashtun groups]] while Iran largely supported the [[Afghan Tajik|Tajik groups]], though they all fought as [[Afghan mujahideen]].<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />\n\nAfter the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, the rivalry between Iran and Pakistan intensified.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yn0TBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=The+Iran-Pakistan+rivalry+intensified+further+following+the+1989+Soviet+withdrawal+from+Afghanistan.+In+the+ensuing+civil+war,+the+Pakistani-backed+Taliban+fought+the+Iranian-supported+Northern+Alliance,+with+the+former+eventually+gaining+control+over+90+percent+of+Afghanistan.&source=bl&ots=LCjBpl4S4r&sig=tD2Gd-cwkpjrbRdWQ-a_YLakGos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT8MSzpqzRAhVBsJQKHfvQB2cQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=The%20Iran-Pakistan%20rivalry%20intensified%20further%20following%20the%201989%20Soviet%20withdrawal%20from%20Afghanistan.%20In%20the%20ensuing%20civil%20war%2C%20the%20Pakistani-backed%20Taliban%20fought%20the%20Iranian-supported%20Northern%20Alliance%2C%20with%20the%20former%20eventually%20gaining%20control%20over%2090%20percent%20of%20Afghanistan.&f=false|title=Iran\u2019s Influence in Afghanistan: Implications for the U.S. Drawdown|last=|first=|publisher=Rand Corporation|year=2014|isbn=9780833085924|location=|pages=25|quote=The Iran-Pakistan rivalry intensified further following the 1989 Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan. In the ensuing civil war, the Pakistani-backed Taliban fought the Iranian-supported Northern Alliance, with the former eventually gaining control over 90 percent of Afghanistan.|via=}}</ref> After 1989, both state's policies in Afghanistan became even more divergent as Pakistan, under [[Benazir Bhutto]], explicitly supported [[Taliban]] forces in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Muhammad Hanif, IPRI\">{{cite web|last=Hanif|first=Muhammad|title=Pakistan-Iran relations: Future challenges|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:kZhdZjH9xdAJ:ipripak.org/articles/latest/pirf.pdf+pakistan+iran+relations&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjOBZ3pm8jDQIk9nLrqU6PHIuNjicvnhs46P35WTwUZI5iJqT_jvANMP6UtSIB-5YmWeoTpGmabFA4Ue67AuMoRBOgn9oEvc5QW_iBGmQhnn4fdgsPW5xixvV_p8xfXfb91Gzlk&sig=AHIEtbT2lXn8dBHWhB-WUnc57xFw4PaGew|work=Islamabad Policy Research Institute|publisher=Muhammad Hanif, IPRI|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> This resulted in a major breach, with Iran becoming closer to India.<ref name=\"Muhammad Hanif, IPRI\" /> Pakistan's support for the Sunni [[Taliban]] organization in Afghanistan became a problem for [[Shia]] Iran which opposed a Taliban-controlled Afghanistan.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Pakistani backed Taliban fought the Iranian backed Northern Alliance in Afghanistan and gained control of 90 percent of that country.<ref name=\":2\" /> As noted by a Pakistani foreign service officer, it was difficult to maintain good relations with Israel, Saudi Arabia, the United States, and Iran at the same time, given Iran's long history of rivalry with these states.<ref name=\"Muhammad Hanif, IPRI\" /> In 1995 Bhutto paid a lengthy state visit to Iran, which greatly relaxed relations. At a public meeting she spoke highly of Iran and Iranian society.<ref name=\"Benazir Bhutto in Iran (Press Release)\">{{cite web|last=Haq|first=Noor-ul-|title=Iran Pakistan relations|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:4vcUM_ZKq64J:ipripak.org/factfiles/ff88.pdf+pakistan+iran+relations&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShaMcs6udbKs5H5g6QA9GWNQ591WUTPRbbiitPq_7rrx0VDJH8iA8bk8t5ANogU8Er88kU4GJ2XF_1M6-Po1u59uWQ2-wNHd4IKXMFVmaQgZvqfy33-gS7Suy9jvMpDioeL734k&sig=AHIEtbQYPb2SCXgficETk0HK35okcLzZCQ|publisher=Benazir Bhutto in Iran (Press Release)|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> However, increasing activity by Shia militants in Pakistan strained relations further.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> This was followed by the Taliban's [[Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif 1997-1998|capture]] of the city of [[Mazar-i-Sharif]] in 1998, in which thousands of Shias were massacred, according to [[Amnesty International]].<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />  The most serious breach in relations came in 1998, after Iran accused [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|Taliban Afghanistan]] of taking [[1998 Iranian diplomats assassination in Afghanistan|11 Iranian diplomats, 35 Iranian truck drivers and an Iranian journalist]] hostage, and later killing them all.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Iran massed over 300,000 troops on the Afghan border and threatened to attack the Taliban government, which it had never recognized.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> This strained relations with Pakistan, as the Taliban were seen as Pakistan's key allies.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> In May 1998, Iran criticized Pakistan for its nuclear testing in the Chagai region, and held Pakistan accountable for global \"[[atomic proliferation]]\".<ref>See: [[Chagai-I]]</ref> New Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] acknowledged his country's nuclear capability on 7 September 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nti.org/e_research/profiles/Pakistan/Nuclear/chronology_2000.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108072216/http://www.nti.org/e_research/profiles/Pakistan/Nuclear/chronology_2000.html|title=NTI: Research Library: Country Profiles: Pakistan|archivedate=8 November 2010|work=NTI publications|accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Bilateral and Multilateral visits in the late 1990s===\n\nIn 1995, [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Benazir Bhutto]] paid a state visit to Iran to lay the groundwork for a memorandum on energy, and begin work on an [[Energy security]] agreement between the two countries. This was followed by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Nawaz Sharif]]'s visit to Tehran for the 8th OIC Summit Conference on 9\u201311 December 1997. While there Sharif held talks with [[President of Iran|President]] [[Mohammad Khatami|Khatami]], with a view to improving bilateral relations, as well as finding a solution to the Afghan crisis.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pakistan and the World (Chronology: October-December 1997)|journal=Pakistan Horizon|date=January 1998|volume=51|issue=1|pages=73\u201390|jstor=41394647|publisher=Pakistan Institute of International Affairs}}</ref>\n\nChief Executive General [[Pervez Musharraf]] paid a two-day visit to Tehran on 8\u20139 December 1999. This was his first visit to Iran (and third international trip) since his [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]] of 12 October 1999 and subsequent seizure of power in Pakistan. In Iran, Musharraf held talks with [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Mohammad Khatami]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistani military ruler meets Iran's Khatami|url=http://iranian.com/Times/1999/Decb/MahmoudAbad/news.html#93|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=The Iranian Times|date=9 December 1999|agency=Reuters}}</ref> and with the [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Iranian Supreme Leader]] [[Ali Khamenei]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran wants end to sectarian violence in Pakistan|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/1999/december/dec9d1999.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=9 December 1999|agency=Reuters}}</ref> This visit was arranged<ref>{{cite news|title=Musharraf leaves for Bahrain, Iran today, Pleads Pak-Iran joint efforts for Afghan peace|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/1999/december/dec8f1999.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=8 December 1999|agency=NNI}}</ref> to allow Musharraf to explain the reasons for his takeover in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saba|first=Sadeq|title=Musharraf on goodwill mission|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/554938.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=8 December 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe meetings included discussions on the situation in Afghanistan, which were intended to lead both countries to \"coordinate the policies of our two countries for encouraging the peace process through reconciliation and dialogue among the Afghan parties\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran & Pakistan to \"coordinate\" their policies towards Afghanistan|url=http://iranian.com/Times/1999/Decb/MahmoudAbad/news.html#94|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=The Iranian Times|date=9 December 1999|agency=AFP}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iran, Pakistan to \"coordinate\" their policies towards Afghanistan|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/1999/december/dec10g1999.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=9 December 1999|agency=AFP}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 Iran accused Pakistani troops of war crimes at [[Bamyan|Bamiyan]] in Afghanistan and claimed that Pakistani warplanes had, in support of the Taliban, bombarded Afghanistan's last Shia stronghold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-09-14/news/9809140197_1_shiite-taliban-sunni|title=Iran Raises Anti-pakistan Outcry|last=Schmetzer|first=Uli|date=14 September 1998|work=Chicago Tribune|quote=KARACHI, Pakistan \u2014 Iran, which has amassed 200,000 troops on the border with Afghanistan, accused Pakistan on Sunday of sending warplanes to strafe and bombard Afghanistan's last Shiite stronghold, which fell hours earlier to the Taliban, the Sunni militia now controlling the central Asian country.|access-date=5 January 2017|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1998/09/16/afghanistan-arena-for-a-new-rivalry/eeedba2f-03b7-4ed6-ba97-91e51e633e96/|title=Afghanistan: Arena For a New Rivalry|last=Constable|first=Pamela|date=16 September 1998|work=The Washington Post|quote=Taliban officials accused Iran of providing military support to the opposition forces; Tehran radio accused Pakistan of sending its air force to bomb the city in support of the Taliban's advance and said Iran was holding Pakistan responsible for what it termed war crimes at Bamiyan. Pakistan has denied that accusation and previous allegations of direct involvement in the Afghan conflict. Also fueling the volatile situation are ethnic and religious rivalries between the Taliban, who are Sunni Muslims of Afghanistan's dominant Pashtun ethnic group, and the opposition factions, many of which represent other ethnic groups or include Shiite Muslims. Iran, a Shiite Muslim state, has a strong interest in promoting that sect; Pakistan, one of the Taliban's few international allies, is about 80 percent Sunni.|access-date=5 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Relations since 2000==\n[[File:Pakistan Consul General met with the Mayor of Mashhad - Seyyed Sowlat Mortazavi and Qazi Habib ul-Rahman 5.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|Pakistan Consul General met with the Mayor of [[Mashhad]]]]\nSince 2000, relations between Iran and Pakistan have begun to normalize, and economic cooperation has strengthened. The [[9-11 terrorist attacks|9/11 terrorist attacks]] on the United States changed the foreign policy priorities of both Iran and Pakistan.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> The [[George W. Bush administration]]'s tough stance forced President Pervez Musharraf to support Washington's [[War on Terror]], which ended Taliban rule in Kabul. Though Iranian officials welcomed the move, they soon found themselves encircled by [[U.S. forces]] in Pakistan, Afghanistan, Central Asia, and the Persian Gulf.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />\n\nPresident Bush's inclusion of the [[Islamic Republic]] as part of an \"[[Axis of Evil]]\" also led some Iranian officials to presume that Tehran might be next in line for [[Covert United States foreign regime change actions|regime change]], ending whatever ''d\u00e9tente'' had occurred in [[Iran\u2013United States relations|Iran\u2013U.S.]] ties under Khatami.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> Bush's emphasis on transformative diplomacy and democratization worried Iranian leaders further.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" />\n\n===Bilateral visits after 2000===\nIn April 2001, the [[Supreme National Security Council|Secretary of Supreme National Security Council]] [[Hassan Rowhani]] (who is President of Iran since August 2013) paid a state visit to Pakistan and met with [[Pervez Musharraf]] and his cabinet.<ref name=\"Dawn News Archives\">{{cite news|last=Alvi|first=Ahmad Hasan|title=Chief Executive calls for stronger defence ties with Iran|url=http://www.lib.virginia.edu/area-studies/SouthAsia/SAserials/Dawn/2001/apr2801.html#chie|accessdate=19 December 2012|newspaper=Dawn News|date=28 April 2001}}</ref> During this visit, Iran and Pakistan agreed to put their differences aside and agree on a broad-based government for Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Dawn News Archives\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan, Iran to promote reconciliation in Afghanistan|url=http://www.afghanistannewscenter.com/news/2001/april/apr27d2001.html|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Afghanistan News Center|date=27 April 2001|agency=Kyodo}}</ref>\n\nIranian Foreign Minister [[Kamal Kharazi]] paid a two-day visit to Islamabad from 29\u201330 November 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hussain|first=Talat|title=Pakistan, Iran seek to settle Afghan differences|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/asiapcf/south/11/29/gen.pakistan.iran/index.html|accessdate=31 August 2013|publisher=CNN|date=29 November 2001}}</ref> Kharazi met with Foreign Minister [[Abdul Sattar (diplomat)|Abdul Sattar]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Kharrazi links peace to broad-based govt|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2001/11/30/top3.htm|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=30 November 2001|author=M. Ziauddin|author2=Faraz Hashmi}}</ref> and President Musharraf.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan, Iran agree to lay gas pipeline: Trade ties being cemented|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2001/12/01/top1.htm|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=1 December 2001|author=Staff Reporter}}</ref> Iran and Pakistan vowed to improve their relations, and agreed to help establish a broad-based, multi-ethnic government under U.N. auspices.<ref>{{cite news|last=Iqbal|first=Nadeem|title=Pakistan, Iran Mend Fences over Afghanistan|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2001/12/politics-pakistan-iran-mend-fences-over-afghanistan/|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=IPS|date=6 December 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe President of Iran, Mohammad Khatami, paid a three-day state visit to Pakistan from 23\u201325 December 2002, the first visit by an Iranian [[head of government]] since 1992.<ref name=\"CNN, December 24, 2002\">{{cite news|last=APP |title=Weapons found during Khatami visit |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-12-24/world/pakistan.khatami_1_kashmir-dispute-kashmiris-on-both-sides-zafarullah-khan-jamali?_s=PM:asiapcf |publisher=CNN |accessdate=25 May 2012 |date=11 March 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227064341/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-12-24/world/pakistan.khatami_1_kashmir-dispute-kashmiris-on-both-sides-zafarullah-khan-jamali?_s=PM%3Aasiapcf |archivedate=27 February 2013 }}</ref> It was a high-level delegation, consisting of the Iranian cabinet, members of the [[Iranian parliament]], [[Vice President of Iran|Iranian Vice-President]] and President Khatami.<ref name=\"CNN, December 24, 2002\" /> This visit was meant to provide a new beginning to Iran\u2013Pakistan relations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Muir|first=Jim|title=Iran and Pakistan: A new beginning|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2601521.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=23 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Akhlaque|first=Qudssia|title=Khatami visit a turning point|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/23/top4.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=23 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zehra|first=Nasim|title=Khatami's visit may add a new dimension to Pakistan ties|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/226913|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Arab News|date=23 December 2002}}</ref> It would also allow for high-level discussions on the future of the [[Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline|Iran\u2013Pakistan\u2013India pipeline]] (IPI) project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Khatami visit to push South Asia pipeline project|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/south/12/23/pakistan.iran/|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=23 December 2002}}</ref> Khatami met, and had detailed discussions, with both President Musharraf<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran seeks to boost Pakistan ties|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2600439.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|publisher=BBC|date=24 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Economic ties top priority, says Khatami|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/24/top1.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=24 December 2002|agency=APP}}</ref> and the new Prime Minister [[Zafarullah Khan Jamali]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran and Pakistan boost ties|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2605309.stm|accessdate=30 August 2013|publisher=BBC|date=25 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=ul Haque|first=Ihtasham|title=Resolution of Kashmir issue soon: Khatami|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/25/top1.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=DAWN|date=25 December 2002}}</ref> Several accords were signed between Iran and Pakistan in this visit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Four accords signed with Iran|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/25/nat12.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=25 December 2002|agency=APP}}</ref> Khatami also delivered a talk on \"Dialogue Among Civilizations,\" at [[The Institute of Strategic Studies]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iranian president lauds Iqbal's poetry|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/25/nat16.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=25 December 2002|agency=APP}}</ref> The presidential delegation initially visited Islamabad, and then followed that up with a visit to Lahore,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hanif|first=Intikhab|title=Khatami concerned at atrocities in Kashmir|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/27/nat27.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=27 December 2002}}</ref> where Khatami also paid his respects at the tomb of Allama Sir [[Muhammad Iqbal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Khatami calls for talks on Kashmir|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/226998|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Arab News|date=26 December 2002}}</ref> A Joint communique was issued by Iran and Pakistan on the conclusion of Khatami's visit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran calls for better strategic relations: Joint communique|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/27/top1.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=27 December 2002|author=Staff Reporter}}</ref> On his return to Tehran, Khatami evaluated the trip as \"positive and fruitful\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Khatami terms visit fruitful|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/12/27/nat47.htm|accessdate=30 August 2013|newspaper=Dawn|date=27 December 2002|agency=PPI}}</ref>\n\nAs in return, Jamali paid a state visit in 2003 where he held talks with economic cooperation, security of the region, and better bilateral ties between Pakistan and Iran.<ref name=\"Daily Times, Wednesday, October 22, 2003\">{{cite web|title=Jamali talks trade with Khatami|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_22-10-2003_pg1_3|work=Daily Times|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>  During this visit, Jamali gave valuable advises to Iranian leadership on their [[Iranian nuclear programme|nuclear programme]] \"against the backdrop of the country's\" negotiations with the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA), and measures to strengthen economic relations between the two countries.<ref name=\"Daily Times, Thursday, October 16, 2003\">{{cite news|author=Shaukat Paracha |title=amali to discuss growing Indo-Iran ties with Khatami |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_16-10-2003_pg7_12 |accessdate=25 May 2012 |newspaper=Daily Times |date=16 October 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050518095538/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_16-10-2003_pg7_12 |archivedate=18 May 2005 }}</ref>\n\n===Military and security===\nIranian support for Pakistan dates back to the 1960s when Iran supplied Pakistan with American military weaponry and spare parts after America cut off their military aid to Pakistan.<ref name=Rubin>{{cite book|last=Rubin|first=Barry|title=Paved With Good Intentions|year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-502805-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/pavedwithgoodint00rubi/page/116 116]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/pavedwithgoodint00rubi/page/116}}</ref> After [[1971 Indo-Pakistani War]], new Prime minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] immediately withdrew Pakistan from [[Central Treaty Organization|CENTO]] and [[Southeast Asia Treaty Organization|SEATO]] after Bhutto thought that the military alliances failed to protect or appropriately assist Pakistan and instead alienated the [[Soviet Union]]. A serious military cooperation between took place during the [[Balochistan conflict|Balochistan insurgency]] phases against the [[Balochistan Liberation Army|armed separatist movement]] in 1974\u201377.<ref name=\"Greenwood Press\">{{cite book|last=Minaham|first=James|title=Encyclopedia of the stateless nations : ethnic and national groups around the world|year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport (Connecticut)|isbn=0-313-31617-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OLKKVXgEpkoC&pg=PA258&dq=pakistan+iran+military+relations&hl=en#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20iran%20military%20relations&f=true|accessdate=30 November 2012|page=google books|chapter=The Dravidians: Baloch}}</ref>  Around ~100,000 Pakistan and Iranian troops were involved in quelling the separatist organizations in Balochistan and successfully put the resistance down in 1978\u201380.<ref name=\"Greenwood Press\" /> In May 2014, the two countries agreed to joint operations against terrorists and drug traffickers in the border regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pakistan-Iran agree for joint Anti-Terrorist and Anti-Drug operations|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/pakistan-iran-agree-for-joint-anti-terrorist-and-anti-drug-operations/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, following a [[2019 Khash\u2013Zahedan suicide bombing|suicide bombing in Khash\u2013Zahedan]] which killed 27 [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] and wounded 13 others, Iranian officials criticised Pakistan. Iranian Major General [[Mohammad Ali Jafari]] asked Pakistan to conduct crack down against armed group Jaish al-Adl before Tehran takes it revenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/02/iran-warns-pakistan-crack-jaish-al-adl-190216071021469.html|title=Iran warns Pakistan to crack down on Jaish al-Adl|date=16 February 2019|work=Al Jazeera}}</ref> In February 2019, Bahram Ghasemi, speaking for the Foreign Ministry of Iran, said it would not tolerate what it saw as Pakistan's \"inability to stop cross-border attacks in Iran\".<ref name=\"Naya2019\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Either Confront Terrorist Groups Or Allow Iranian Forces To Enter\u2019: Iran Threatens Pakistan |url=https://www.nayadaur.tv/2019/02/either-confront-terrorist-groups-or-allow-iranian-forces-to-enter-iran-threatens-pakistan |website=Naya Daur |accessdate=20 February 2019 |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> Pakistan, in turn, offered Iran cooperation in investigating the bombing, and expressed sympathy for the victims of the attack. A Pakistani delegation was due to travel to Iran.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1464488 Pakistan offers cooperation to Iran over probe into attack], ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|The Dawn]]''.</ref>\n\n===Iran's view on Kashmir issue===\nOn 19 November 2010 Iran's [[Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah Ali Khamenei appealed to Muslims worldwide to back the freedom struggle in [[Jammu and Kashmir]], equating the dispute with the ongoing conflicts of the Greater Middle East region.\n\n\"Today the major duty of the elite of the Islamic Ummah is to provide help to the Palestinian nation and the besieged people of [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]], to sympathize and provide assistance to the nations of Afghanistan, Pakistan, Iraq and [[Occupied Kashmir]], to engage in struggle and resistance against the aggressions of the [[United States]], the [[Zionist Regime]]...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahazi-islami.com/news-events/index.asp?NewsID=257|title=Mahazi Islami - News & Events|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iran-times.com/khamenehi-says-kashmir-oppressed/|title=Khamenehi says Kashmir oppressed|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> He further said that Muslims should be united and \"spread awakening and a sense of responsibility and commitment among Muslim youth throughout Islamic communities\".<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/twice-in-7-days-iran-talks-of-oppressed-kashmir/articleshow/59454492.cms|title=Twice in seven day, Iran talk of oppressed Kashmiri|accessdate=5 July 2017|publisher=Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"India Today\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/irans-supreme-leader-khamenei-rakes-up-kashmir-bogey-twice-in-two-weeks-1022519-2017-07-05|title=Iran's supreme leader Khamenei rakes up Kashmir bogey twice in two weeks|accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"The wire\">{{cite news|url=https://thewire.in/diplomacy/iran-khamenei-kashmir|title=For the First Time in Seven Years, Ayatollah Khamenei Rakes Up Kashmir|accessdate=27 June 2017|publisher=The wire}}</ref><ref name=\"FirstPost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/irans-ayatollah-ali-khamenei-urges-muslims-in-kashmir-to-repudiate-oppressors-3747153.html|title=Iran's Ayatollah Ali Khamenei urges Muslims in Kashmir to 'repudiate oppressors'|accessdate=26 June 2017|publisher=FirstPost}}</ref>\n\nThe thrust of his speech was directed at Israel, India, and the US, but also made a veiled reference to Pakistan's nuclear program:\n\n\"The US and the West are no longer the unquestionable decision-makers of the Middle East that they were two decades ago. Contrary to the situation 20 years ago, nuclear know-how and other complex technologies are no longer considered inaccessible daydreams for Muslim nations of the region.\"\n\nHe said the US was bogged down in Afghanistan and \"is hated more than ever before in disaster-stricken Pakistan\".\n\nA former president of Iran (1981\u201389), Khamenei succeeded Ayatollah Khomeini as the spiritual head of the Iranian people. A staunch supporter of Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, Khamenei is believed to be highly influential in Iran's foreign policy.\n\nKhamenei visited [[Jammu and Kashmir]] in the early 1980s and delivered a sermon at Srinagar's Jama Masjid mosque.\n\nIn 2017, Iran's leader Ayatollah Khamenei said that [[Kashmiris]] are being oppressed. He also urged Muslim world to \"openly support people of [[Kashmir]] and repudiate oppressors and tyrants who attacked people in [[Ramadan]]\".<ref name=\"Times of India\"/><ref name=\"India Today\"/><ref name=\"The wire\"/><ref name=\"FirstPost\"/>\n\nBy 2019, after India had removed the autonomy of Indian Kashmir, Pakistan's Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]] thanked Iran's Supreme Leader, for his support of Pakistan's position on the Kashmir issue.<ref>https://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/513803-PM-Imran-thanks-Iranian-Supreme-Leader-for-supporting-Kashmir-issue-</ref>\n\n===Atoms for Peace cooperation===\n{{Further|Atoms for Peace}}\n\nSince 1987, Pakistan has steadily blocked any Iranian acquisition of [[nuclear weapons]]; however, Pakistan has wholeheartedly supported Iran's viewpoint on the issue of its [[Nuclear program of Iran|nuclear energy program]], maintaining that \"Iran has the right to develop its nuclear program within the ambit of NPT.\" In 1987 Pakistan and Iran signed an agreement on civil nuclear energy cooperation, with [[Zia-Ul-Haq]] personally visiting Iran as part of its \"Atoms for Peace\" program.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\">{{cite web|title=A.Q. Khan and onward proliferation from Pakistan|work=The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, Zia calculated that this cooperation with Iran was purely a \"civil matter\", necessary for maintaining good relations with Tehran.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\" /> According to IAEA, Iran wanted to purchase fuel-cycle technology from Pakistan, but was rebuffed.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\" /> Zia did not approve any further nuclear deals, but one of Pakistan's [[Abdul Qadeer Khan|senior scientists]] did secretly hand over a sensitive report on centrifuges in 1987\u201389.<ref name=\"The International Institute For Strategic Studies (IISS)\" />\n\nIn 2005, [[IAEA]] evidence showed that Pakistani cooperation with Iran's nuclear program was limited to \"non-military spheres\",<ref name=\"Columbia Univ Pr\" /> and was peaceful in nature.<ref name=\"Columbia Univ Pr\" /> Tehran had offered as much as $5 billion for nuclear weapons technology in 1990, but had been firmly rejected. Centrifuge technology was transferred in 1989; since then, there have been no further atoms for peace agreements.<ref name=\"Columbia Univ Pr\">{{cite book|last=Hussain|first=Zahid|title=Frontline Pakistan The Struggle With Militant Islam.|year=2008|publisher=Columbia Univ Pr|location=Berkeley, Calif.|isbn=978-0-231-14225-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cD36RbtSKNkC&pg=PA166&dq=pakistan+iran+military+relations&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=true}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, IAEA evidence revealed that the centrifuge designs transferred in 1989 were based on early commercial power plant technology, and were riddled with technical errors; the designs were not evidence of an active nuclear weapons program.<ref>Linzer, Dafna (23 August 2005). \"No Proof Found of Iran Arms Program; Uranium Traced to Pakistani Equipment\". The Washington Post. Retrieved 20 September 2009.</ref>\n\n===Non-belligerent policy and official viewpoint===\nDifficulties have included disputes over trade, and political position. While Pakistan's [[Foreign policy of Pakistan|foreign policy]] maintains balanced relations with [[Pakistan\u2013Saudi Arabia relations|Saudi Arabia]], the [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations|United States]], and the [[Pakistan\u2013European Union relations|European Union]], Iran tends to warn against it, and raised concerns about Pakistan's absolute backing of the [[Taliban]] during the [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1996\u20132001)|fourth phase]] of [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|civil war]] in [[Afghanistan]] in the last years of the 20th century.<ref name=\"Middle East Quarterly\" /> \nThrough a progressive reconciliation and chaotic diplomacy, both countries come closer to each other in last few years. In the changing security environment, Pakistan and Iran boosted their ties by maintaining the warmth in the relationship without taking into account the pressures from international actors.<ref>http://www.opinion-maker.org/2012/03/pak-iran-relations-the-changing-scenario/</ref>\n\nOn Iran's nuclear program and its own relations with Iran, Pakistan adopted a policy of [[Neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]], and played a subsequent [[non-belligerent]] role in easing the tension in the region. Since 2006, Pakistan has been strategically advising Iran on multiple occasions to counter the international pressure on its nuclear program to subsequently work on civil nuclear power, instead of active nuclear weapons program.<ref name=\"Dawn News Archives, 2006\">{{cite news|title=2006: Shaukat Aziz told Ahmedinejad to abandon Iran\u2019s nuclear weapons program|url=http://dawn.com/2011/07/09/2006-shaukat-aziz-told-ahmedinejad-to-abandon-irans-nuclear-weapons-program/|accessdate=30 May 2012|newspaper=Dawn News|date=9 July 2011}}</ref> On international front, Pakistan has been a great advocate for Iranian usage of nuclear energy for economics and civil infrastructure while it steadily stop any Iranian acquisition of nuclear weapons, fearing another nuclear armed race with Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Geo Pakistan\">{{cite news|title=Pakistan supports peaceful use of Nuclear energy by Iran: PM Gilani|url=http://www.geo.tv/GeoDetail.aspx?ID=42475|accessdate=26 August 2012|newspaper=Geo Pakistan|date=1 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130419071118/http://www.geo.tv/GeoDetail.aspx?ID=42475|archivedate=19 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech at [[Harvard University]] in 2010, the Pakistan's [[Foreign Minister of Pakistan|foreign minister]] [[Shah Mehmood Qureshi]] justified Iran's nuclear program as peaceful and argued that Iran had \"no justification\" to pursue [[nuclear weapons]], citing the lack of any immediate threat to Iran, and urged Iran to \"embrace overtures\" from the United States. Qureshi also observed that Iran had signed the [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty]] and should respect the treaty.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran doesn't need nuclear weapons: Qureshi|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/64577/iran-doesnt-need-nuclear-weapons-qureshi/|accessdate=31 December 2011|newspaper=International Herald Tribune|date=19 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIran and Pakistan have been described as competitors for influence in the Middle East by some geo-political analysts, who argue a nuclear armed Iran could further agitate Pakistan.<ref>https://books.google.ca/books?id=hOyMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=iranian+influence+in+pakistan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFlbXDs97mAhVNbs0KHT40Clw4FBDoAQhuMAg#v=onepage&q=iranian%20influence%20in%20pakistan&f=false</ref>\n\nBoth countries also have a history of mutual distrust, accusing each other of supporting religious and ethnic rebels within each other's borders.<ref>https://www.dw.com/en/after-soleimani-killing-irans-proxy-war-to-impact-afghanistan-and-pakistan/a-51918670</ref>\n\n===Flood relief===\nDuring the [[2019 Iran floods]], Pakistan's [[National Disaster Management Authority (Pakistan)|National Disaster Management Authority]], on the order of country's Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]] sent 32 tonnes of relief goods to Iran. The consignment comprising two shipments contained 500 tents, 3,300 blankets and emergency medical kits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.mehrnews.com/news/143977/Pakistan-dispatches-humanitarian-assistance-to-flood-hit-Iran|title=Pakistan dispatches humanitarian assistance to flood hit Iran|date=10 April 2019|work=Mehr News Agency|access-date=7 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411153757/https://en.mehrnews.com/news/143977/Pakistan-dispatches-humanitarian-assistance-to-flood-hit-Iran|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1947574/1-pakistan-sends-humanitarian-aid-flood-hit-iran/|title=Pakistan sends humanitarian aid to flood-hit Iran|date=10 April 2019|work=Express Tribune}}</ref> The relief goods were transferred using two [[C-130]] aircraft. Previously Pakistan's Foreign Office (FO) spokesperson, Dr. Muhammad Faisal, condoled with the families of the victims. The spokesperson further claimed that Pakistan is ready to provide humanitarian assistance to Iran in rescue effort. He claimed that people of Pakistan stand in solidarity with Iranian people in their difficult time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/04/08/pakistan-expresses-grief-over-iran-floods/|title=Pakistan sends two C-130 aircrafts &#91;sic&#93; to Iran with flood relief goods|date=9 April 2019|work=Pakistan Today|access-date=7 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411163539/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/04/08/pakistan-expresses-grief-over-iran-floods/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Trade and Economics==\n[[File:Iran-Pakistan-India.JPG|thumb|right|Modified image of Iran-Pakistan national gas pipeline.]]\n\nRelations between Iran and Pakistan improved after the removal of the Taliban in 2002, but tensions remain. Pakistan has been under a strong influence of [[Saudi Arabia]] in its competition with Shiite majority Iran for influence across the broader Islamic world, which it already has in its allied nations Lebanon and Syria. Iran considers northern and western Afghanistan as its sphere of influence since its population is Persian [[Dari (Eastern Persian)|Dari]] speaking. Pakistan considers southern and eastern Afghanistan as its sphere of influence since it is Pashto and Baloch speaking such as the [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and [[Baluchistan (Pakistan)|Baluchistan]], respectively.\n\n===Free Trade Agreement===\nIn 2005, Iran and Pakistan had conducted US$500 million of trade. The land border at [[Taftan (Balochistan)|Taftan]] is the conduit for trade in electricity and oil. Iran is extending its railway network towards [[Taftan (Balochistan)|Taftan]].\n\nThe [[Iran-Pakistan-India gas pipeline|Iran-Pakistan-India pipeline]] (IPI Pipeline) is currently under discussion; though India backed out from the project. The [[Indian government]] was under pressure by the [[United States]] against the [[Iran-Pakistan-India pipeline|IPI pipeline]] project, and appears to have heeded [[Foreign policy of the United States|American policy]] after India and the United States proceeded to sign the [[Indo-US civilian nuclear agreement|nuclear deal]]. In addition, the [[Sanctions on Iran|international sanctions]] on Iran due to its controversial [[Nuclear program of Iran|nuclear program]] could also become a factor in derailing [[Iran-Pakistan-India pipeline|IPI pipeline]] project altogether.\n\nTrade between the two countries has increased by \u00a31.4 billion in 2009.<ref name=\"The Nation, 2012\">{{cite news|last=Iranian Embassy|title=Pak-Iran economic relations|url=http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/columns/18-Feb-2012/pak-iran-economic-relations|accessdate=27 November 2012|newspaper=The Nation, 2012|date=18 February 2012}}</ref> In 2007-08, annual Pakistan merchandise trade with Iran consisted of $256 million in imports and $218.6 million in export, according to [[World Trade Organization|WTO]].<ref name=\"World Trade Organization\">{{cite web|last=WTO|title=Iran's Economic Partner|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:83mfoFym4XwJ:www.fpcci.com.pk/trade-with-countries/Iran.pdf+pakistan+iran+trade+statistics&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgtr_nqUg5eYfIv0Xp9ETk4yZn46-rXm20_1-qkg21VS7RLXOvvPLDcxQ-9zoD6un8Fo4qq5Qb5xIdM3HJpPiC2FSnH5OGsr8z6i0jUTm4sGIlD-H8gM0BhJ5BC20U_0ugw7xCO&sig=AHIEtbSZt8_AZDYrteEQ7wgNb2w2Hau1qA|publisher=World Trade Organization|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Bilateral trade===\nOn 12 January 2001, Pakistan and Iran formed a \"Pakistan-Iran Joint Business Council\" (PIJB) body on trade disputes.<ref name=\"Dawn Archives, 2001\">{{cite news|last=Reporter|title=Pakistan, Iran form body on trade disputes|url=http://www.lib.virginia.edu/area-studies/SouthAsia/SAserials/Dawn/2001/jan1301.html#iran|accessdate=19 December 2012|newspaper=Dawn Archives, 2001|date=13 January 2001}}</ref> The body works on to encourage the privatization in Pakistan and economic liberalization on both sides of the countries.<ref name=\"Dawn Archives, 2001\" /> In 2012, the bilateral trade exceeded $3 billion.<ref name=\"Daily Pakistan 2012\">{{cite news|last=Staff Report|title=Pakistan to consider barter trade with Iran|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C10%5C10%5Cstory_10-10-2012_pg5_5|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper=Daily Pakistan 2012|date=10 October 2012}}</ref> Official figures from the [[State Bank of Pakistan]] for fiscal year 2011-12 indicate imports of $124 million and exports of $131 million, which had collapsed to $36 million of exports to Iran and less than $1 million of imports for the year to April 2015. In 2011, the trade between Iran and Pakistan stood at less than $1 billion and the common geographical borders as well as religious affinities are among other factors, which give impetus to enhanced level of trade.<ref name=\"Daily Pakistan 2012\" /> According to the media reports, Iran is the second-largest market of [[Rice production in Pakistan|Basmati rice]] of Pakistan, ranking after Iraq.<ref name=\"Daily Pakistan July 29\">{{cite news|last=Staff Report|title=Pakistan to consider barter trade with Iran|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C07%5C29%5Cstory_29-7-2012_pg5_5|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper=Daily Pakistan 29 July|date=29 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Techno-Entrepreneurship===\nMomentum of improvement of economic and political relationships between Iran and Pakistan has created a wave of bilateral agreements between Iranian and Pakistan authorities. Techno-entrepreneurship is the highly trending topic of discussion in the global development and in ECO region (Pakistan-Iran-Turkey), a lot of joint projects have been executed since 2016. ScienceTech+ Center was the first joint techno-entrepreneurship center, which was established by the Pakistani and Iranian entrepreneurs in a joint agreement between CODE Entrepreneurship Consultants Ltd (Pakistan) and Ideparvaran MashreghQazal Ltd (Iran).<ref name=\" \u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u062c\u0634\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0622\u067e \u0633\u0627\u06cc\u0646\u0633 \u062a\u06a9 \u067e\u0644\u0627\u0633\">{{cite news|last=Reporter|title=\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u062c\u0634\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0622\u067e \u0633\u0627\u06cc\u0646\u0633 \u062a\u06a9 \u067e\u0644\u0627\u0633|url=http://www.iribnews.ir/fa/news/1670974/%D9%86%D8%B4%D8%B3%D8%AA-%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%B1%DB%8C-%D8%AC%D8%B4%D9%86%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87-%DA%A9%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B1%DB%8C%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%A8%DB%8C%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%84%D9%84%DB%8C-%D8%B3%D8%A7%DB%8C%D9%86%D8%B3-%D8%AA%DA%A9-%D9%BE%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%B4%D9%87%D8%AF#iran|accessdate=22 Khordad 1396|newspaper= \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0635\u062f\u0627\u0648\u0633\u06cc\u0645\u0627, 2016|date=22 Khordad 1396}}</ref><ref name=\"ScienceTech+ Center\">{{cite web|last=Staff Report|title=Sciencetechplus International Accelerator|url=http://www.sciencetechplus.com|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> Several events under this platform are being organized by the [Pakistani in Iran] and Iranian authorities under the title of KarafarinShow in Iran, Pakistan and Turkey.<ref name=\"KarafarinShow\">{{cite web|last=KarafarinShow|title=KarafarinShow|url=https://www.karafarinshow.com|publisher=ScienceTech+|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Effects of US sanctions on Iran====\n{{Main|U.S. sanctions against Iran}}\n\nThe U.S. economic sanctions on Iran regarding their [[Iranian nuclear program|nuclear program]] generally affected Pakistan's industrial sector.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\">{{cite news|last=Our Correspondents|title=Pakistan loses Iran\u2019s mango market|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/395445/pakistan-loses-irans-mango-market/|accessdate=5 January 2013|newspaper=Tribune Express|date=5 January 2013}}</ref>  The fruit industry of Pakistan have reportedly lost a lucrative market in Iran, where at least 30,000 tons of [[mango]] were exported previously, as a result of the trade embargo imposed by the United States on Tehran.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\" /> According to the statistics by Pakistan, the fruit industry and the exporters could not export around $10 million worth of mango during the current season.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\" /> The [[Ministry of Commerce (Pakistan)|Ministry of Commerce (MoCom)]] has been in direct contact with the [[US Department of Agriculture]] to resolve the issue through diplomatic channels.<ref name=\"Tribune Express\" />\n\n==Energy==\n\n===Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline===\n{{Main|Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline|Energy Security}}\n\nDiscussions between the governments of [[Government of Iran|Iran]] and [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistan]] started in 1994 for the gas pipelines and energy security.<ref name=downstream1>{{cite news|url=http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=10718|title=IPI Implementation Nearing 'Final Stage' \u2013 Pakistani Official|work=Downstream Today|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=8 May 2008|accessdate=10 May 2008}}</ref> A preliminary agreement was signed in 1995 by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Benazir Bhutto]] and [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani]], in which, this agreement foresaw construction of a pipeline from [[South Pars / North Dome Gas-Condensate field|South\u2013North Pars gas field]] to [[Karachi]] in Pakistan. Later, Iran made a proposal to extend the pipeline from Pakistan into India. In February 1999, a preliminary agreement between Iran and India was signed.<ref name=chaudhary>{{cite web|url= http://www.american.edu/TED/iranpipeline.htm|title= Iran to India Natural Gas Pipeline: Implications for Conflict Resolution & Regionalism in India, Iran, and Pakistan|publisher= [[School of International Service]]|first=Shamila N.|last=Chaudhary|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nIran has the world's second largest gas reserves, after [[Russia]], but has been trying to develop its oil and gas resources for years, due to sanctions by the West. However, the project could not take off due to different political reasons, including the new gas discoveries in [[List of natural gas fields|Miano, Sawan and Zamzama]] gas fields of Pakistan. The Indian concerns on pipeline security and Iranian indecisiveness on different issues, especially prices. The Iran-Pakistan-India (denoted as IPI Pipeline) project was planned in 1995 and after almost 15 years India finally decided to quit the project in 2008 despite severe energy crises in that country.\n\nIn February 2007, India and Pakistan agreed to pay Iran [[United States Dollar|US$]]4.93 per million [[British thermal unit|BTUs]] (US$4.67/GJ) but some details relating to price adjustment remained open to further negotiation.<ref name=irandaily1>{{cite news|url=http://iran-daily.com/1386/2880/html/economy.htm#s238905|title=Peace Pipeline Contract Soon, Gas Flow by 2011|newspaper=Iran Daily|date=1 July 2007|accessdate=10 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506083012/http://iran-daily.com/1386/2880/html/economy.htm#s238905|archivedate=6 May 2008}}</ref> Since 2008, Pakistan began facing severe criticism from the United States over any kind of energy deal with Iran. Despite delaying for years the negotiations over the IPI gas pipeline project, Pakistan and Iran have finally signed the initial agreement in Tehran in 2009. The project, termed as the peace pipeline by officials from both the countries, was signed by President Zardari and President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad of Iran. In 2009, India withdrew from the project over pricing and security issues, and after signing another civilian nuclear deal with the [[United States]] in 2008.<ref name=reuters170310>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE62G12C20100317\n|title=Pakistan, Iran sign deal on natural gas pipeline|first=Zeeshan|last=Haider|date=17 March 2010|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=upi190310a>{{cite news|url= http://www.upi.com/Science_News/Resource-Wars/2010/03/19/Pakistan-gas-pipeline-is-Irans-lifeline/UPI-27741269029633/|title=Pakistan gas pipeline is Iran's lifeline|work=[[United Press International|UPI]]|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref> However, in March 2010 India called on Pakistan and Iran for trilateral talks to be held in May 2010 in [[Tehran]].<ref name=upi190310b>{{cite news|url= http://www.upi.com/Science_News/Resource-Wars/2010/03/19/New-Delhi-calls-for-IPI-talks/UPI-15881269006235/|title=New Delhi calls for IPI talks|work=[[United Press International|UPI]]|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the initial design of the project, the 2,700&nbsp;km long pipeline was to cover around 1,100&nbsp;km in Iran, 1,000&nbsp;km in Pakistan and around 600&nbsp;km in India, and the size of the pipeline was estimated to be 56 inches in diameter. However, as India withdrew from the project the size of the pipeline was reduced to 42 [[inches|inch]]. In April 2008, Iran expressed interest in the [[People's Republic of China]]'s participation in the project.<ref name=downstream3>{{cite news|url= http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=10460|title=Ahmadinehjad Would Welcome Chinese Role In Gas Pipeline|publisher=Downstream Today|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=28 April 2008|accessdate=10 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nSince as early as in 2005, China and Pakistan are already working on a proposal for laying a trans-Himalayan pipeline to carry Middle Eastern crude oil to western China.<ref name=\"dailytimes.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010/08/08/story_8-8-2010_pg5_10|title=DailyTimes - Your Right To Know|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> Beijing has been pursuing Tehran and Islamabad for its participation in the pipeline project and willing to sign a bilateral agreement with Iran. China and Pakistan are already working on a proposal for laying a trans-Himalayan pipeline to carry Middle Eastern crude oil to western China.<ref name=\"dailytimes.com.pk\" /> In August 2010, Iran invited [[Bangladesh]] to join the project.<ref name=fe150810>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/more.php?news_id=109098&date=2010-08-15|title=Iran invites Bangladesh to join cross-border gas grid|first=Humayan|last=Kabir|newspaper=[[Financial Express (Bangladesh)|The Financial Express]]|date=15 August 2010|accessdate=20 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Power Transmissions===\nTehran has provided [[Euros|\u20ac]]50 million for laying of 170[[kilometer|Km]] transmission line for the import of 1000MW of electricity from Iran in 2009. Pakistan is already importing 34MW of electricity daily from Iran. The imported electricity is much cheaper than the electricity produced by the Independent Power Producers (IPPs) because [[Ministry of Petroleum of Iran#Gasoline subsidies|Iran subsidises oil and gas]] which feed the power plants.<ref>[http://www.iran-daily.com/1388/3366/html/economy.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408063452/http://www.iran-daily.com/1388/3366/html/economy.htm|date=8 April 2009}}</ref> Iran has also offered to construct a motorway between Iran and Pakistan connecting the two countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010\\08\\17\\story_17-8-2010_pg7_24|title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |publisher=Daily Times|date=17 August 2010|accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Diplomacy and role in mediation==\nSince Iran has no diplomatic relations with the [[United States]]; the Iranian interests section in the United States is represented by the Embassy of Pakistan Embassy in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. Iranian nuclear scientist, [[Shahram Amiri]], thought to have been abducted by [[CIA]] from [[Saudi Arabia]], took sanctuary in the [[Embassy of Pakistan in Washington, D.C.|Pakistan Embassy in Washington, D.C]]. The Iranian government claimed the United States has trumped up charges they were involved with the [[9/11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2010/07/201071353210347523.html |title=Iranian scientist surfaces in US \u2013 Americas|work=Al Jazeera|date=13 July 2010|accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomatic missions===\n\n====Iranian missions in Pakistan====\nIran's chief diplomatic mission to Pakistan is the Iranian Embassy in Islamabad. The embassy is further supported by many Consulates located throughout in Pakistan.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\">{{cite web|title=Iranian presence in Pakistan|url=http://www.iranembassy.pk/en/embassy-home/location.html|publisher=Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref>  The Iranian government supports Consulates in several major Pakistan's cities including: [[Karachi]]<sup>\u2021</sup>, [[Lahore]]<sup>\u2021</sup>, [[Quetta]]<sup>\u2021</sup>, [[Peshawar]]<sup>\u2021</sup>.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" /> Iranian government maintains a cultural consulate-general,  Persian Research Center, and ''Sada-o-Sima'' center, all in Islamabad.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" /> Other political offices includes cultural centers in [[Lahore]]<sup>\u2020</sup>, Karachi<sup>\u2020</sup>, [[Rawalpindi]]<sup>\u2020</sup>, Peshawar<sup>\u2020</sup>, Quetta<sup>\u2020</sup>, [[Hyderabad, Pakistan|Hyderabad]]<sup>\u2020</sup>, and [[Multan]]<sup>\u2020</sup>.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" />\n* \u2021 ''denotes mission is [[Consulate General]]''\n* \u2020 ''denotes mission is ''Khana-e-Farhang'' (lit. culture center)''\n\nThere is also an [[Iran Air]] corporate office located in [[Karachi Metropolitan Corporation]] site.<ref name=\"Consulate-Generals of Iran in Pakistan\" />\n\n===Immigration===\n{{Main|Iranians in Pakistan|Pakistanis in Iran|Pakistan Technical Assistance Programme}}\n\nIn the [[Balochistan (region)|Balochistan region]] of southeastern Iran and western Pakistan, the [[Balochi people]] routinely travel the area with little regard for the official border, causing considerable problems for the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps|Iranian Guards Corps]] and the [[Frontier Corps]] of [[Pakistan]]. Both countries have ongoing conflicts with [[Balochistan conflict|Balochi separatist]] groups.\n\nSince 2010, there has been an increase in meetings between senior figures of both governments as they attempt to find a regional solution to the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghan war]] and continue discussions on a proposed [[Iran\u2013Pakistan gas pipeline]] and an [[Economic Cooperation Organization]].<ref name=\"Pakistan Today\">{{cite news|last=Staff reporter|first=w|title=Container Train line|url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2011/12/economic-cooperation-organisation-insists-upon-container-train-reactivation|accessdate=26 October 2013|newspaper=Pakistan Today|date=12 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIranian media delegations have been visiting Pakistan annually since 2004, with many journalists settling in Pakistan. These visits have played an effective role in promoting mutual understanding and projecting a positive image of Pakistan in Iran.<ref name=\"Pakistan Embassy, Tehran\">{{cite web|last=. Khalid Aziz Babar, Ambassador of Pakistan to Tehran|title=Cultural relations of Pakistan and Iran|url=http://www.mofa.gov.pk/iran/contents.aspx?type=statements&id=2|publisher=Pakistan Embassy, Tehran|accessdate=26 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nNotable Pakistani political figures [[Benazir Bhutto|Benazir]], [[Murtaza Bhutto|Murtaza]], and [[Shahnawaz Bhutto]] were half [[Iranian Kurds]] on their [[Nusrat Bhutto|mother's side]].\n\n====Pakistani missions in Iran====\nPakistan's chief diplomatic mission to Iran is the Pakistani embassy in Tehran. It is further supported by two consulates-general located throughout Iran.<ref name=\"Embassy of Pakistan Presence\">{{cite web|title=Embassy of Pakistan in Iran|url=http://www.mofa.gov.pk/iran/contents.aspx?type=statements&id=2|publisher=Embassy of Pakistan Presence|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> The [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistani government]] supports its [[Consul (representative)|consulates]] in [[Mashhad]] and [[Zahedan|Zahidan]].<ref name=\"Embassy of Pakistan Presence\" />\n\n==Education==\nThe [[Pakistan International School and College Tehran|Pakistan International School and College - Tehran]] aims to serve and accommodate additional educational needs for Pakistani families living in Tehran.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iran|Pakistan}}\n* [[Iran-Pakistan border]]\n* [[Nuclear program of Iran]]\n* [[Iran-Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n* [[Persian language in South Asia]]\n* [[Pakistani Armed Forces#Middle Eastern Countries|Pakistan Armed Forces\u2014 Iranian Contingent]]\n* [[List of statistically superlative countries]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Relations of Iran and Pakistan}}\n* [http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/HA13Df03.html Asia Times on Iran-Pakistan relations]\n* Schoresch Davoodi & Adama Sow: ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20080216052138/http://www.aspr.ac.at/epu/research/rp_0807.pdf The Political Crisis of Pakistan in 2007]'' \u2013 [[European University Center for Peace Studies|EPU]] Research Papers: Issue 08/07, Stadtschlaining 2007 \u2013 Research Paper which also describes the relations between Pakistan and Iran\n* [http://www.dawn.com/2009/01/01/top6.html Pakistan, Iran to boost cooperation in power sector]\n*  Pattanayak, Dr. Satyanarayan : ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20131030071936/http://www.vijbooks.com/book/164/Dr-Satyanarayan-Pattanayak/Iran-s-Relations-with-Pakistan-A-Strategic-Analysis/9789380177656.html Iran's Relations with Pakistan: A Strategic Analysis]'' \u2013 [[United Services Institution of India|USI]] Research Book, May 2012 \u2013 A well researched book focuses on various facets of the Iran Pakistan relationship in a long term perspective by analyzing them under various Phases.\n\n{{Iran\u2013Pakistan relations}}\n{{Foreign relations of Iran}}\n{{Foreign relations of Pakistan}}\n\n <!-- fixcategory -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iran-Pakistan Relations}}\n[[Category:1947 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013Pakistan relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Iran|Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Walz.rice", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed colour coding of HDI status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran%E2%80%93Pakistan_relations"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Oceania}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania\n| map1            = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Oceania]]\n| first_case      = [[Melbourne, Victoria]], [[Australia]]\n| arrival_date    = 25 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=25|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  =  698<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| deaths          =  31<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| confirmed_cases =  6,328<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = 8<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Oceania]] in January 2020.\n\n==Pandemic by country==\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Australia (Density).svg|thumb|Map of the outbreak in Australia]]\n\n=== Australia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia}}\n\nOn 1 March, it was reported that a 78-year-old man from [[Western Australia]],\nwho was a passenger on the ''Diamond Princess'', had become the first person to die from coronavirus in Australia.<ref>[https://7news.com.au/travel/coronavirus/western-australian-man-becomes-first-person-in-australia-to-die-from-coronavirus-c-723547 Western Australian man becomes first person in Australia to die from coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301012352/https://7news.com.au/travel/coronavirus/western-australian-man-becomes-first-person-in-australia-to-die-from-coronavirus-c-723547 |date=1 March 2020 }} 7News 1 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-current-situation-and-case-numbers|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) current situation and case numbers|date=18 March 2020|website=Australian Government Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211190436/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert|archive-date=11 February 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 1st April, the death toll in Australia stands at 20 with approximately 4,711 cases reported.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Chile===\n====Easter Island====\nOn 19 March, the local government of [[Easter Island|Easter Island (Rapa Nui)]] ordered a lockdown of the island and requested [[LATAM Airlines]] to evacuate all tourists on the island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clarin.com/viajes/coronavirus-chile-moai-isla-pascua-cuarentena_0_ZyvSBEtTU.html|title=Coronavirus en Chile: los moai de Isla de Pascua, en cuarentena|work=Clar\u00edn|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-AR}}</ref> However, on 24 March, the first case of coronavirus was reported on the island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/de-origen-autoctono-rapa-nui-confirma-primer-contagio-de-coronavirus-en-la-isla_20200324/|title=De origen aut\u00f3ctono: Rapa Nui confirma primer contagio de coronavirus en la isla|publisher=CNN Chile|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n=== Fiji ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Fiji}}\nAs of 2 April, there are 7 confirmed cases in Fiji.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-confirms-latest-cases-of-covid-19/|title=Fiji confirms latest cases of COVID-19|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n{{Further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n\n==== French Polynesia ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Polynesia}}\nOn 11 March, the first case in French Polynesia was confirmed. The first patient was [[Maina Sage]], a member of the French National Assembly.<ref>[https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411544/french-polynesia-records-first-coronavirus-case] 11 March 2020</ref>\n\n==== New Caledonia ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Caledonia}}\n\nAs of 25 March, there have been fourteen cases in New Caledonia.<ref name=\"Covid19 New Caledonia\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Ninth case in New Caledonia confirmed |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412512/covid-19-ninth-case-in-new-caledonia-confirmed |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324091953/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412512/covid-19-ninth-case-in-new-caledonia-confirmed |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== New Zealand ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\nAs of 3 April, New Zealand has reported 868 confirmed and probable cases.<ref name=\"Covid-19 current cases NZ\">{{cite web |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-current-cases |title=COVID-19 - current cases |date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The first case, confirmed on 26 February, was in a citizen who had arrived from Iran.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/single-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand |title=Single case of COVID-19 confirmed in New Zealand |access-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228055315/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/single-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand |archive-date=28 February 2020 |website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand}}</ref> The second case was in a citizen who had recently traveled to northern Italy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/second-case-covid-19-confirmed-nz |title=Second Case of COVID-19 Confirmed in NZ |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 |website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304003940/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/second-case-covid-19-confirmed-nz |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first local transmission of the virus happened on 4 March, located in Auckland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410982/coronavirus-update-family-of-nz-s-third-case-had-travelled-to-iran |title=Coronavirus update: Family of NZ's third case had travelled to Iran |date=5 March 2020 |website=RNZ |language=en-nz |access-date=6 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306152838/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410982/coronavirus-update-family-of-nz-s-third-case-had-travelled-to-iran |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 29 March, New Zealand reported its first fatality, a woman in her 70s from the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast region]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Newshub: Coronavirus: First New Zealand death recorded.\n|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-first-new-zealand-death-recorded.html |newspaper=Newshub |date=29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020 |first1=Dan |last1=Satherley |first2=Mark |last2=Quinlivan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Manch |first1=Thomas |last2=Devlin |first2=Collette |title=Coronavirus: New Zealand has 514 cases \u2013 one person dead on West Coast |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120655743/coronavirus-update-on-all-of-government-covid19-national-response-at-1pm |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329003814/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120655743/coronavirus-update-on-all-of-government-covid19-national-response-at-1pm |archivedate=29 March 2020}}</ref> As of 3 April, 103 people have recovered.<ref name=\"Covid-19 current cases NZ\" />\n\nAs of 3 April, no cases have been reported in the associated states of [[Cook Islands]] and [[Niue]] and the dependent territories of [[Tokelau]] and the [[Ross Dependency]] (see below).\n\n=== Papua New Guinea ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Papua New Guinea}}\nOn 20 March, the first case in Papua New Guinea was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.pngfacts.com/2020/03/png-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus.html|title=PNG Confirms first Case of Coronavirus-COVID -19|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSwabs were taken and sent to the Medical Research Institute in Goroka for testing. Three announcements followed. First the Health Minister Jelta Wong declared a probable case, and Prime Minister [[James Marape]] followed up by declaring the result as negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postcourier.com.pg/health-minister-says-papua-new-guinea-has-a-probable-case-of-covid-19/|title=Health Minister says Papua New Guinea has a probable case of COVID-19|date=18 March 2020|website=Post Courier|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.looppng.com/node/90799|title=\u2018Probable\u2019 Lae COVID-19 case tests negative|first=Loop|last=Author|date=18 March 2020|website=Loop PNG|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Further tests were conducted and the prime minister confirmed the positive result for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/kramerreportpng/posts/1926235824179381|title=Kramer Report|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Police Minister Bryan Kramer then stated on Facebook that the inconsistent results were due to faulty test equipment, and that requests had been made for further testing to be conducted in Melbourne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://devpolicy.org/covid-19-the-situation-so-far-and-challenges-for-png-20200327/|title=COVID-19: the situation so far and challenges for PNG|first=Michael|last=Kabuni|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{Further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n==== Guam ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam}}\nAs of 3 April, the US territory of Guam has had 82 confirmed cases of the virus, with several further potential cases under, and 3 deaths\ninvestigation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi-local/73-local/2765-2-confirmed-covid-19-cases-in-nmi |title=NMI has 2 confirmed Covid-19 cases|date=28 March 2020|publisher=Marianas Variety|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/cnmi-confirms-cases/article_b4a4e706-70de-11ea-b844-539b94ecdc52.html |title=CNMI confirms 2 cases|date=29 March 2020|publisher=The Guam Daily Post|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tomas |first1=Jojo Santo |title=Five more test positive for coronavirus, Guam total at 82 |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/02/guam-coronavirus-update-covid-19-cases-april-2/5110400002/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=[[Pacific Daily News]] |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Hawaii ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hawaii}}\nAs of 19 March, there have been 22 confirmed cases in the state of Hawaii.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2020/03/17/latest-white-house-wants-send-sizable-checks-americans-boost-economy/|title=City closes all city parks, golf courses and Honolulu Zoo|last=|first=|date=|website=Hawaii News Now|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Northern Mariana Islands====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Northern Mariana Islands}}\nOn 28 March the islands confirmed their first two coronavirus cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411869/pacific-nations-take-further-measures-against-coronavirus |title=Pacific countries, already hard hit by epidemics, take extreme coronavirus measures |date=16 March 2020 |website=RNZ |url-status=live|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention in other countries and territories==\n===Australia===\n====Norfolk Island====\nAs of 20 March Norfolk Island has not had any cases. As a precautionary measure the government has imposed a 32-day travel ban and declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-17/norfolk-island-stops-tourists-to-stop-coronavirus-outbreak/12064666 |title=Coronavirus fears on Norfolk Island prompt travel ban as state of emergency declared|date=17 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Administrator [[Eric Hutchinson (politician)|Eric Hutchinson]] stated that the measures were necessary due to the remote island's extremely limited health capacity.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n===France===\n====Wallis and Futuna====\nAs of 28 March the territory has remained corona free. On 4 March [[Wallis and Futuna]] turned away a cruise ship over fears of infection; the possibility of denying entry to another ship by the end of the month is also under consideration.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410932/coronavirus-cruise-ship-banned-from-wallis-and-futuna |title=Coronavirus: Cruise ship banned from Wallis and Futuna |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 |agency=RNZ}}</ref> Incoming flights have also been curtailed, save for those delivering essential supplies.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wallis-et-futuna.gouv.fr/Actualites/Mise-en-place-des-mesures-de-prevention-contre-l-epidemie-de-Covid-19-dans-les-iles-Wallis-et-Futuna|title=Mise en place des mesures de pr\u00e9vention contre l'\u00e9pid\u00e9mie de Covid-19 dans les \u00eeles Wallis et Futuna |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020 |publisher=Government of Wallis and Futuna}}</ref>\n\n=== Kiribati ===\nOn 1 February, the [[government of Kiribati]] put all visas from China on hold and required new arrivals to fill in a health form and travellers from countries with the coronavirus to go through a self-quarantine period.<ref name=\"Kiribati\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408618/coronavirus-kiribati-blocks-chinese-travellers |title=Coronavirus: Kiribati blocks Chinese travellers |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131235410/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408618/coronavirus-kiribati-blocks-chinese-travellers |archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> Despite not having any cases, on 28 March President [[Taneti Maamau]] declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kiribatiupdates.com.ki/president-declared-kiribati-a-state-of-public-emergency-for-convid-19/|title=President declared Kiribati a state of public emergency for convid-19 |date=29 March 2020 |website=Kiribati Updates |url-status=live|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Marshall Islands ===\nOn 24 January, the [[Marshall Islands|Republic of the Marshall Islands]] issued a travel advisory that requires any visitors to the country to have spent at least 14 days in a country free of the virus.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnson |first=Giff |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408140/marshall-islands-bans-direct-travel-from-china |title=Marshall Islands bans direct travel from China |date=25 January 2020 |work=Radio New Zealand |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125183541/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408140/marshall-islands-bans-direct-travel-from-china |archive-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> On 1 March, the ban was extended to China, Macau, Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea, Italy and Iran.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnson |first=Giff |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410714/marshall-islands-prepares-for-coronavirus-to-come-like-a-freight-train |title=Marshall Islands prepares for coronavirus to come 'like a freight train' |date=1 March 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301124311/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410714/marshall-islands-prepares-for-coronavirus-to-come-like-a-freight-train |archive-date=1 March 2020 |agency=RNZ}}</ref>\n\nAs of 18 March, all incoming international travel has been temporarily suspended, as well as some intra-island flight services.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411999/coronavirus-two-more-cases-confirmed-in-guam |title=Coronavirus: Two more cases confirmed in Guam|date=19 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Micronesia ===\nBy 3 February, [[David W. Panuelo]], President of the [[Federated States of Micronesia]], had signed a declaration banning Micronesian citizens from travelling to China and other affected countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408617/fsm-marshall-islands-step-up-coronavirus-travel-bans |title=FSM, Marshall Islands step up coronavirus travel bans |date=1 February 2020 |website=RNZ |access-date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201121506/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408617/fsm-marshall-islands-step-up-coronavirus-travel-bans |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy 5 March, Micronesia had introduced a strict travel ban, banning anyone who had been in China anytime since January 2020 \u2014 or had been in any other affected country in the last 14 days \u2014 from entering Micronesia.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/micronesia-drastic-coronavirus-travel-ban.html |title=The Most Drastic Anti-Coronavirus Travel Ban in the World |last=Withers |first=Rachel |date=5 March 2020 |website=Slate Magazine |access-date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309110543/https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/micronesia-drastic-coronavirus-travel-ban.html |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 18 March, all schools in the country have also been closed.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===Nauru===\nAs of 28 March, there have been no cases. The government has, however, declared a national emergency as a preventive measure, suspending all but one weekly flight to the country and instituting a 14-day quarantine for all arrivals.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412004/coronavirus-sweeping-restrictions-introduced-across-the-pacific |title=Coronavirus: Sweeping restrictions introduced across the Pacific |date=17 March 2020 |website=RNZ |url-status=live|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand Associated Countries===\n====Cook Islands====\nAs of 28 March, the Cook Islands have not had any cases. As a precautionary measure, all most international and many inter-island flights have been cancelled, and non-essential surgeries cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411909/coronavirus-stricter-measures-introduced-in-guam-cook-islands |title=Coronavirus: Stricter measures introduced in Guam, Cook Islands|date=17 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412054/cook-islands-ramps-up-covid-19-prevention-and-mitigation |title=Cook Islands ramps up Covid-19 prevention and mitigation|date=18 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12318529 |title=Coronavirus: A look at cases and restrictions in the Pacific|date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March Prime Minister [[Henry Puna]] announced that 'Code Yellow' measures would be in place in the islands, by which public gatherings are restricted.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412580/covid-19-cook-islands-to-move-to-code-yellow |title=Covid-19: Cook Islands to move to Code Yellow|date=25 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Niue====\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in Niue. As a precautionary measure the government has banned visitors from highly affected countries.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n====Tokelau====\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in Tokelau. As a precautionary measure boats arriving from affected countries have been banned from landing.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> On 19 March all incoming travel was suspended, except for Tokelauans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tokelau.org.nz/Bulletin/March+2020/Travel+restrictions+and+entry+requirements+for+COVID+19+revised+19th+March+2020.html |title=Travel restrictions and entry requirements for COVID 19 revised 19th March 2020|publisher=Government of Tokelau|date=19 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Palau ===\nThe President of [[Palau]] [[Thomas Remengesau Jr.]] issued an executive order suspending all charter flights from China, [[Macau]], and Hong Kong from 1\u201329 February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/palau-to-ban-flights-from-china/article_7f3edea2-4193-11ea-b924-efb7bf56dedc.html |title=Palau to ban flights from China |date=21 January 2020 |website=The Guam Daily Post glish |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129014005/https://www.postguam.com/news/local/palau-to-ban-flights-from-china/article_7f3edea2-4193-11ea-b924-efb7bf56dedc.html |archive-date=29 January 2020 |access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Schools will be also be shut starting in April.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n=== Samoa ===\nTravel into [[Samoa]] has been increasingly restricted in an effort to prevent the spread of COVID-19 into the country. Before entering the country, people must have spent at least 14 days in a country free of the virus, as well as complete a medical clearance.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wilson |first=Soli |url=https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/56845 |title=Coronavirus screening mandatory for visitors to Samoa |date=26 January 2020 |work=Samoa Observer |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128052005/https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/56845 |archive-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Two Samoan nationals who had briefly stopped in China were placed into quarantine on 28 January for two weeks at the Faleolo District Hospital.{{update inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408269/two-men-in-quarantine-in-samoa-over-coronavirus-fears |title=Two men in quarantine in Samoa over coronavirus fears |date=28 January 2020 |work=Radio New Zealand |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127215814/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408269/two-men-in-quarantine-in-samoa-over-coronavirus-fears |archive-date=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12303785 |title=Two men in quarantine in Samoa over virus fears |date=27 January 2020 |work=The New Zealand Herald |access-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211023357/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12303785 |archive-date=11 February 2020 |issn=1170-0777}}</ref> Three students and a former student were evacuated{{when|date=February 2020}} with assistance from New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/update-samoan-students-in-wuhan-china/ |title=Samoan students in Wuhan, China \u2013 Government of Samoa |last=Tamaalii |first=Funefe'ai Dikaiosune Atoa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222140810/http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/update-samoan-students-in-wuhan-china/ |archive-date=22 February 2020 |access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On 9 February, eight Samoan nationals travelling from India were denied entry into the country after catching a connecting flight in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dreaver |first=Barbara |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/world/samoan-coronavirus-restrictions-see-eight-citizens-refused-entry-after-flying-through-singapore |title=Samoan coronavirus restrictions see eight citizens refused entry after flying through Singapore |date=15 February 2020 |work=[[TVNZ]] |access-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229235452/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/world/samoan-coronavirus-restrictions-see-eight-citizens-refused-entry-after-flying-through-singapore |archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, Samoa banned all [[cruise ship]]s from visiting the country.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410113/samoa-places-blanket-ban-on-cruise-ship-visits |title=Samoa places blanket ban on cruise ship visits |date=22 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222215027/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410113/samoa-places-blanket-ban-on-cruise-ship-visits |archive-date=22 February 2020 |agency=Radio New Zealand}}</ref> On 29 February, the government announced restrictions on air travel, with the frequency of international flights into Samoa being reduced from 2 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/special-health-travel-advisory-in-relation-to-the-2019-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Special health travel advisory in relation to the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) |last=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 February 2020 |publisher=Government of Samoa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229235455/http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/special-health-travel-advisory-in-relation-to-the-2019-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ |archive-date=29 February 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Samoa reported its first suspected case of the coronavirus, an individual who had traveled from New Zealand. Bodily samples from the person were taken to [[Melbourne]] for testing.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tamaaliii |first1=Funefe'ai |title=Ministry of Health Coronavirus (COVID-19) Update 18/03/2020 |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/03/ministry-of-health-coronavirus-covid-19-update-18-03-2020/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=Government of Samoa |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 10-20 day wait for Samoa test result |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412091/coronavirus-10-20-day-wait-for-samoa-test-result |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> In response, the Samoan Government required all travelers including Samoan citizens to undergo a medical checkup upon returning.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tamaalii |first1=Funefe'ia |title=UPDATED TRAVEL ADVISORY NOVEL CORONAVIRUS (COVID-2019) |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/03/updated-travel-advisory-novel-coronavirus-covid-2019-2/ |publisher=Government of Samoa |accessdate=19 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200319072542/http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/03/updated-travel-advisory-novel-coronavirus-covid-2019-2/ |archivedate=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, Samoa declared a state of emergency, closing its borders to all but returning citizens.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tonga and Samoa declare states of emergency because of Covid-19 |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412240/tonga-and-samoa-declare-states-of-emergency-because-of-covid-19 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the Samoan Health Ministry confirmed that eight suspected cases of the coronavirus were being tested. All of these individuals had a prior history of travel or contact with relatives who traveled abroad.<ref>{{cite news |title=Eight suspected cases of coronavirus under investigation in Samoa |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/world/eight-suspected-cases-coronavirus-under-investigation-in-samoa |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[1 News]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kerr |first1=Florence |title=Coronavirus: Samoa tests eight suspected cases of Covid-19 |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120468609/coronavirus-samoa-tests-eight-suspected-cases-of-covid19 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Prime Minister of Samoa|Prime Minister]] [[Tuilaepa Aiono Sailele Malielegaoi]] announced that the first suspected case of COVID-19 had been cleared of the virus. While he confirmed that six of the eight suspected cases had tested negative for the coronavirus, they were still awaiting test results for the remaining two patients from New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news |title=Test for suspected Covid-19 case in Samoa comes back negative |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412317/test-for-suspected-covid-19-case-in-samoa-comes-back-negative |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> That same day, Samoa also suspended air travel with Australia and restricted flights from New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kerr |first1=Florence |title=Coronavirus: Samoa suspends all flights from Australia |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120472548/coronavirus-samoa-suspends-all-flights-from-australia |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, it was reported that a total of seven suspected cases of the coronavirus were awaiting testing in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news |title=Samoa waits for seven COVID-19 tests |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412513/samoa-waits-for-seven-covid-19-tests |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324091730/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412513/samoa-waits-for-seven-covid-19-tests |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Prime Minister Tuila'epa Sa'ilele Malielegaoi announced that individuals that didn't adhere to the COVID-19 restriction will be fined.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412587/samoa-to-fine-people-who-don-t-adhere-to-covid-19-restrictions|title=Samoa to fine people who don't adhere to Covid-19 restrictions|date=2020-03-25|work=[[Radio New Zealand]]|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On 26 March, the Samoan Government introduced lockdown measures including banning fishing boats from entering Samoa and fining businesses that breached the quarantine. Only cargo ships carrying goods and petrol will be allowed to enter Samoa.<ref>{{cite news |title=Samoa officially on lock down |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412647/samoa-officially-on-lock-down |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Solomon Islands===\nAs of 28 March, there have been no cases. As a precautionary measure the government has stepped up checks on incoming visitors, and introduced restrictions on visitors who have visited countries deemed high risk.<ref name=\"rnzPacific 16 March 2020\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411869/pacific-nations-take-further-measures-against-coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |website=RNZ |url-status=live|title=Pacific nations take further measures against coronavirus|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March Prime Minister [[Manasseh Sogavare]] suspended all flights into the country, and declared a precautionary state of emergency in [[Honiara]], by which most entertainment venues would be closed (churches are exempt from the order).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412792/covid-19-solomons-closes-borders-honiara-now-emergency-zone |website=RNZ |url-status=live|title=Covid-19: Solomons closes borders, Honiara now emergency zone|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, Franco Rodie, the permanent secretary of the [[Ministry of Education and Human Resources Development]], ordered the closure of all schools in the Solomon Islands.<ref>{{cite news |title=All schools ordered to close in Solomon Islands |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/413013/all-schools-ordered-to-close-in-solomon-islands |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Tonga===\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in the country. As a precautionary measure, various travel and quarantining restrictions have been put in place.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Cruise ships and yachts have also been banned from docking in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://matangitonga.to/2020/03/17/tonga-toughens-travel-advisory |title=Tonga toughens travel advisory |date=17 March 2020 |website=Matangi Tonga |url-status=live|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March Prime Minister [[Pohiva Tu'i'onetoa]] announced that the country would be under a lock-down 29 March-5 April.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412708/tonga-declares-lockdown-starting-this-weekend |title=Tonga declares lockdown starting this weekend |website=RNZ |date=27 March 2020|url-status=live|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Tuvalu===\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in the country. As a precautionary measure, visitors will not be allowed to land without first undergoing 14 days of isolation in a third party state.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> Circa 26 March the acting governor general declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412625/covid-19-pacific-summary|title=Covid-19: Pacific summary|date=2020-03-26|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n====Pitcairn Islands====\nAs of 28 March, there have been no cases in the British territory. As a precautionary measure, all passenger services to the islands have been suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.visitpitcairn.pn/index.html|title=Pitcairn Islands Tourism|website=Pitcairn Islands Tourism|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n====American Samoa====\nAs of 24 March, the US territory has not had any cases. On 6 March, the American Samoan government introduced new entry restrictions including restricting flight numbers and requiring travelers from Hawaii to spend 14 days in Hawaii and obtain a health clearance from health authorities.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Samoa tightens entry requirements over Covid-19 |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411111/american-samoa-tightens-entry-requirements-over-covid-19 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=6 March 2020}}</ref> On 11 March, a government task-force was set up to deal with the virus and quarantining measures have been put in place for incoming visitors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411472/american-samoa-establishes-covid-19-govt-taskforce |title=American Samoa establishes Covid-19 govt taskforce|access-date=17 March 2020|work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, half of the 210 passengers on a returning [[Hawaiian Airlines]] flight were required to self-quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Half of flight's passengers to self-quarantine in American Samoa |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411725/half-of-flight-s-passengers-to-self-quarantine-in-american-samoa |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Following a trip to the US mainland, Governor [[Lolo Matalasi Moliga]] self-isolated as a precautionary measure on 16 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411793/covid-19-american-samoa-governor-self-isolates-as-a-precaution |title=Covid-19: American Samoa governor self-isolates as a precaution|access-date=17 March 2020|work=[[Radio New Zealand]]|date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, [[Iulogologo Joseph Pereir]]a, executive assistant to the American Samoa Governor and the head of the territory's coronavirus task force, acknowledged that the territory did not have facilities to test samples of the Covid-19 virus, having to rely on testing facilities in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Georgiev |first1=Peter |last2=Kaplan |first2=Adiel |title=American Samoa's coronavirus conundrum: No way to test |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-care/american-samoa-s-coronavirus-conundrum-no-way-test-n1167776 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vanuatu===\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in the country. Travel restrictions and quarantine measures have been put in place for those entering the country.<ref name=\"rnzPacific 16 March 2020\"/> On 22 March, Vanuatu's health authorities confirmed that tests for a resort worker with a suspected case of coronavirus had returned negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19 tests in Samoa, Vanuatu come back negative |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412317/covid-19-tests-in-samoa-vanuatu-come-back-negative |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=22 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324091322/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412317/covid-19-tests-in-samoa-vanuatu-come-back-negative |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March President [[Tallis Obed Moses]] declared a state of emergency in the country.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news |title=Vanuatu declares State of Emergency over Covid-19 |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412660/vanuatu-declares-state-of-emergency-over-covid-19 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> A tourist on a cruise ship visiting the island of [[Aneityum]] had tested positive for the virus, prompting a lockdown on the island.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Oceania]]\n*[[Bubonic plague]] Four deaths in [[Fremantle]], Western Australia, 1903\n*[[Smallpox]] Epidemic in News South Wales, Australia, 1828 \n*[[Influenza]] \n*[[Measles]] 40,000 died in 1875 Fiji Measles outbreak\n*[[Spanish flu]] 1918 flu pandemic, killed 17 to 50 million people worldwide\n*[[Epidemiology of HIV/AIDS|HIV/AIDS pandemic]]\n*[[2019 Samoa measles outbreak]] 83 deaths\n*[[2019\u20132020 dengue fever epidemic]] 276 cases and one death were reported in the Marshall Islands<ref>[https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/398139/marshalls-confirms-first-dengue-death Marshalls confirms first dengue death] by Giff Johnson, RNZ, 5 Sep 2019, retrieved 27 Mar 2020</ref> Outbreaks were also reported in Palau, the Federated States of Micronesia, the Cook Islands, Tuvalu, and the Philippines.<ref>[https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/397502/who-says-2019-worse-than-usual-for-dengue-in-pacific WHO says 2019 'worse than usual' for dengue in Pacific] RNZ, 26 Aug 2019, retrieved 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n{{End div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Update Live |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/coronavirus-updates-live-covid-19-cases-surpass-800-000-worldwide-nsw-and-qld-border-force-officials-test-positive-20200331-p54ft0.html |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/ ncov \u2013 CSSE] - Map of the expansion of the virus in Europe and in the world\n*[https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-current-situation-and-case-numbers Department of Health] - Case numbers as confirmed by the Australian government\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by continent|Oceania]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Oceania|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Oceania]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Oceania}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania\n| map1            = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Oceania]]\n| first_case      = [[Melbourne, Victoria]], [[Australia]]\n| arrival_date    = 25 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=25|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  =  698<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| deaths          =  31<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| confirmed_cases =  6,328<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = 8<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Oceania]] in January 2020.\n\n==Pandemic by country==\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Australia (Density).svg|thumb|Map of the outbreak in Australia]]\n\n=== Australia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia}}\n\nOn 1 March, it was reported that a 78-year-old man from [[Western Australia]],\nwho was a passenger on the ''Diamond Princess'', had become the first person to die from coronavirus in Australia.<ref>[https://7news.com.au/travel/coronavirus/western-australian-man-becomes-first-person-in-australia-to-die-from-coronavirus-c-723547 Western Australian man becomes first person in Australia to die from coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301012352/https://7news.com.au/travel/coronavirus/western-australian-man-becomes-first-person-in-australia-to-die-from-coronavirus-c-723547 |date=1 March 2020 }} 7News 1 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-current-situation-and-case-numbers|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) current situation and case numbers|date=18 March 2020|website=Australian Government Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211190436/https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert|archive-date=11 February 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 1st April, the death toll in Australia stands at 20 with approximately 4,711 cases reported.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Chile===\n====Easter Island====\nOn 19 March, the local government of [[Easter Island|Easter Island (Rapa Nui)]] ordered a lockdown of the island and requested [[LATAM Airlines]] to evacuate all tourists on the island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clarin.com/viajes/coronavirus-chile-moai-isla-pascua-cuarentena_0_ZyvSBEtTU.html|title=Coronavirus en Chile: los moai de Isla de Pascua, en cuarentena|work=Clar\u00edn|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-AR}}</ref> However, on 24 March, the first case of coronavirus was reported on the island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/de-origen-autoctono-rapa-nui-confirma-primer-contagio-de-coronavirus-en-la-isla_20200324/|title=De origen aut\u00f3ctono: Rapa Nui confirma primer contagio de coronavirus en la isla|publisher=CNN Chile|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n=== Fiji ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Fiji}}\nAs of 2 April, there are 7 confirmed cases in Fiji.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-confirms-latest-cases-of-covid-19/|title=Fiji confirms latest cases of COVID-19|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n{{Further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n\n==== French Polynesia ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Polynesia}}\nOn 11 March, the first case in French Polynesia was confirmed. The first patient was [[Maina Sage]], a member of the French National Assembly.<ref>[https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411544/french-polynesia-records-first-coronavirus-case] 11 March 2020</ref>\n\n==== New Caledonia ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Caledonia}}\n\nAs of 25 March, there have been fourteen cases in New Caledonia.<ref name=\"Covid19 New Caledonia\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Ninth case in New Caledonia confirmed |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412512/covid-19-ninth-case-in-new-caledonia-confirmed |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324091953/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412512/covid-19-ninth-case-in-new-caledonia-confirmed |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== New Zealand ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\nAs of 3 April, New Zealand has reported 868 confirmed and probable cases.<ref name=\"Covid-19 current cases NZ\">{{cite web |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-current-cases |title=COVID-19 - current cases |date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The first case, confirmed on 26 February, was in a citizen who had arrived from Iran.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/single-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand |title=Single case of COVID-19 confirmed in New Zealand |access-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228055315/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/single-case-covid-19-confirmed-new-zealand |archive-date=28 February 2020 |website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand}}</ref> The second case was in a citizen who had recently traveled to northern Italy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/second-case-covid-19-confirmed-nz |title=Second Case of COVID-19 Confirmed in NZ |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 |website=Ministry of Health, New Zealand |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304003940/https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/media-releases/second-case-covid-19-confirmed-nz |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first local transmission of the virus happened on 4 March, located in Auckland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410982/coronavirus-update-family-of-nz-s-third-case-had-travelled-to-iran |title=Coronavirus update: Family of NZ's third case had travelled to Iran |date=5 March 2020 |website=RNZ |language=en-nz |access-date=6 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306152838/https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/410982/coronavirus-update-family-of-nz-s-third-case-had-travelled-to-iran |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 29 March, New Zealand reported its first fatality, a woman in her 70s from the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast region]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Newshub: Coronavirus: First New Zealand death recorded.\n|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/03/coronavirus-first-new-zealand-death-recorded.html |newspaper=Newshub |date=29 March 2020 |access-date=29 March 2020 |first1=Dan |last1=Satherley |first2=Mark |last2=Quinlivan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Manch |first1=Thomas |last2=Devlin |first2=Collette |title=Coronavirus: New Zealand has 514 cases \u2013 one person dead on West Coast |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120655743/coronavirus-update-on-all-of-government-covid19-national-response-at-1pm |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329003814/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120655743/coronavirus-update-on-all-of-government-covid19-national-response-at-1pm |archivedate=29 March 2020}}</ref> As of 3 April, 103 people have recovered.<ref name=\"Covid-19 current cases NZ\" />\n\nAs of 3 April, no cases have been reported in the associated states of [[Cook Islands]] and [[Niue]] and the dependent territories of [[Tokelau]] and the [[Ross Dependency]].\n\n=== Papua New Guinea ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Papua New Guinea}}\nOn 20 March, the first case in Papua New Guinea was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.pngfacts.com/2020/03/png-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus.html|title=PNG Confirms first Case of Coronavirus-COVID -19|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSwabs were taken and sent to the Medical Research Institute in Goroka for testing. Three announcements followed. First the Health Minister Jelta Wong declared a probable case, and Prime Minister [[James Marape]] followed up by declaring the result as negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postcourier.com.pg/health-minister-says-papua-new-guinea-has-a-probable-case-of-covid-19/|title=Health Minister says Papua New Guinea has a probable case of COVID-19|date=18 March 2020|website=Post Courier|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.looppng.com/node/90799|title=\u2018Probable\u2019 Lae COVID-19 case tests negative|first=Loop|last=Author|date=18 March 2020|website=Loop PNG|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Further tests were conducted and the prime minister confirmed the positive result for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/kramerreportpng/posts/1926235824179381|title=Kramer Report|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Police Minister Bryan Kramer then stated on Facebook that the inconsistent results were due to faulty test equipment, and that requests had been made for further testing to be conducted in Melbourne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://devpolicy.org/covid-19-the-situation-so-far-and-challenges-for-png-20200327/|title=COVID-19: the situation so far and challenges for PNG|first=Michael|last=Kabuni|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{Further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n==== Guam ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam}}\nAs of 3 April, the US territory of Guam has had 82 confirmed cases of the virus, with several further potential cases under, and 3 deaths\ninvestigation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi-local/73-local/2765-2-confirmed-covid-19-cases-in-nmi |title=NMI has 2 confirmed Covid-19 cases|date=28 March 2020|publisher=Marianas Variety|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/cnmi-confirms-cases/article_b4a4e706-70de-11ea-b844-539b94ecdc52.html |title=CNMI confirms 2 cases|date=29 March 2020|publisher=The Guam Daily Post|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tomas |first1=Jojo Santo |title=Five more test positive for coronavirus, Guam total at 82 |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/02/guam-coronavirus-update-covid-19-cases-april-2/5110400002/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=[[Pacific Daily News]] |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Hawaii ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hawaii}}\nAs of 19 March, there have been 22 confirmed cases in the state of Hawaii.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2020/03/17/latest-white-house-wants-send-sizable-checks-americans-boost-economy/|title=City closes all city parks, golf courses and Honolulu Zoo|last=|first=|date=|website=Hawaii News Now|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Northern Mariana Islands====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Northern Mariana Islands}}\nOn 28 March the islands confirmed their first two coronavirus cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411869/pacific-nations-take-further-measures-against-coronavirus |title=Pacific countries, already hard hit by epidemics, take extreme coronavirus measures |date=16 March 2020 |website=RNZ |url-status=live|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention in other countries and territories==\n===Australia===\n====Norfolk Island====\nAs of 20 March Norfolk Island has not had any cases. As a precautionary measure the government has imposed a 32-day travel ban and declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-17/norfolk-island-stops-tourists-to-stop-coronavirus-outbreak/12064666 |title=Coronavirus fears on Norfolk Island prompt travel ban as state of emergency declared|date=17 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Administrator [[Eric Hutchinson (politician)|Eric Hutchinson]] stated that the measures were necessary due to the remote island's extremely limited health capacity.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n===France===\n====Wallis and Futuna====\nAs of 28 March the territory has remained corona free. On 4 March [[Wallis and Futuna]] turned away a cruise ship over fears of infection; the possibility of denying entry to another ship by the end of the month is also under consideration.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410932/coronavirus-cruise-ship-banned-from-wallis-and-futuna |title=Coronavirus: Cruise ship banned from Wallis and Futuna |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 |agency=RNZ}}</ref> Incoming flights have also been curtailed, save for those delivering essential supplies.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wallis-et-futuna.gouv.fr/Actualites/Mise-en-place-des-mesures-de-prevention-contre-l-epidemie-de-Covid-19-dans-les-iles-Wallis-et-Futuna|title=Mise en place des mesures de pr\u00e9vention contre l'\u00e9pid\u00e9mie de Covid-19 dans les \u00eeles Wallis et Futuna |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020 |publisher=Government of Wallis and Futuna}}</ref>\n\n=== Kiribati ===\nOn 1 February, the [[government of Kiribati]] put all visas from China on hold and required new arrivals to fill in a health form and travellers from countries with the coronavirus to go through a self-quarantine period.<ref name=\"Kiribati\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408618/coronavirus-kiribati-blocks-chinese-travellers |title=Coronavirus: Kiribati blocks Chinese travellers |date=1 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131235410/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408618/coronavirus-kiribati-blocks-chinese-travellers |archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> Despite not having any cases, on 28 March President [[Taneti Maamau]] declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kiribatiupdates.com.ki/president-declared-kiribati-a-state-of-public-emergency-for-convid-19/|title=President declared Kiribati a state of public emergency for convid-19 |date=29 March 2020 |website=Kiribati Updates |url-status=live|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Marshall Islands ===\nOn 24 January, the [[Marshall Islands|Republic of the Marshall Islands]] issued a travel advisory that requires any visitors to the country to have spent at least 14 days in a country free of the virus.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnson |first=Giff |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408140/marshall-islands-bans-direct-travel-from-china |title=Marshall Islands bans direct travel from China |date=25 January 2020 |work=Radio New Zealand |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125183541/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408140/marshall-islands-bans-direct-travel-from-china |archive-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> On 1 March, the ban was extended to China, Macau, Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea, Italy and Iran.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnson |first=Giff |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410714/marshall-islands-prepares-for-coronavirus-to-come-like-a-freight-train |title=Marshall Islands prepares for coronavirus to come 'like a freight train' |date=1 March 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301124311/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410714/marshall-islands-prepares-for-coronavirus-to-come-like-a-freight-train |archive-date=1 March 2020 |agency=RNZ}}</ref>\n\nAs of 18 March, all incoming international travel has been temporarily suspended, as well as some intra-island flight services.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411999/coronavirus-two-more-cases-confirmed-in-guam |title=Coronavirus: Two more cases confirmed in Guam|date=19 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Micronesia ===\nBy 3 February, [[David W. Panuelo]], President of the [[Federated States of Micronesia]], had signed a declaration banning Micronesian citizens from travelling to China and other affected countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408617/fsm-marshall-islands-step-up-coronavirus-travel-bans |title=FSM, Marshall Islands step up coronavirus travel bans |date=1 February 2020 |website=RNZ |access-date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201121506/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408617/fsm-marshall-islands-step-up-coronavirus-travel-bans |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy 5 March, Micronesia had introduced a strict travel ban, banning anyone who had been in China anytime since January 2020 \u2014 or had been in any other affected country in the last 14 days \u2014 from entering Micronesia.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/micronesia-drastic-coronavirus-travel-ban.html |title=The Most Drastic Anti-Coronavirus Travel Ban in the World |last=Withers |first=Rachel |date=5 March 2020 |website=Slate Magazine |access-date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309110543/https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/micronesia-drastic-coronavirus-travel-ban.html |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 18 March, all schools in the country have also been closed.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===Nauru===\nAs of 28 March, there have been no cases. The government has, however, declared a national emergency as a preventive measure, suspending all but one weekly flight to the country and instituting a 14-day quarantine for all arrivals.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412004/coronavirus-sweeping-restrictions-introduced-across-the-pacific |title=Coronavirus: Sweeping restrictions introduced across the Pacific |date=17 March 2020 |website=RNZ |url-status=live|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand Associated Countries===\n====Cook Islands====\nAs of 28 March, the Cook Islands have not had any cases. As a precautionary measure, all most international and many inter-island flights have been cancelled, and non-essential surgeries cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411909/coronavirus-stricter-measures-introduced-in-guam-cook-islands |title=Coronavirus: Stricter measures introduced in Guam, Cook Islands|date=17 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412054/cook-islands-ramps-up-covid-19-prevention-and-mitigation |title=Cook Islands ramps up Covid-19 prevention and mitigation|date=18 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12318529 |title=Coronavirus: A look at cases and restrictions in the Pacific|date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March Prime Minister [[Henry Puna]] announced that 'Code Yellow' measures would be in place in the islands, by which public gatherings are restricted.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412580/covid-19-cook-islands-to-move-to-code-yellow |title=Covid-19: Cook Islands to move to Code Yellow|date=25 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Niue====\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in Niue. As a precautionary measure the government has banned visitors from highly affected countries.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n====Tokelau====\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in Tokelau. As a precautionary measure boats arriving from affected countries have been banned from landing.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> On 19 March all incoming travel was suspended, except for Tokelauans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tokelau.org.nz/Bulletin/March+2020/Travel+restrictions+and+entry+requirements+for+COVID+19+revised+19th+March+2020.html |title=Travel restrictions and entry requirements for COVID 19 revised 19th March 2020|publisher=Government of Tokelau|date=19 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Palau ===\nThe President of [[Palau]] [[Thomas Remengesau Jr.]] issued an executive order suspending all charter flights from China, [[Macau]], and Hong Kong from 1\u201329 February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/palau-to-ban-flights-from-china/article_7f3edea2-4193-11ea-b924-efb7bf56dedc.html |title=Palau to ban flights from China |date=21 January 2020 |website=The Guam Daily Post glish |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129014005/https://www.postguam.com/news/local/palau-to-ban-flights-from-china/article_7f3edea2-4193-11ea-b924-efb7bf56dedc.html |archive-date=29 January 2020 |access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Schools will be also be shut starting in April.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n=== Samoa ===\nTravel into [[Samoa]] has been increasingly restricted in an effort to prevent the spread of COVID-19 into the country. Before entering the country, people must have spent at least 14 days in a country free of the virus, as well as complete a medical clearance.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wilson |first=Soli |url=https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/56845 |title=Coronavirus screening mandatory for visitors to Samoa |date=26 January 2020 |work=Samoa Observer |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128052005/https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/56845 |archive-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Two Samoan nationals who had briefly stopped in China were placed into quarantine on 28 January for two weeks at the Faleolo District Hospital.{{update inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408269/two-men-in-quarantine-in-samoa-over-coronavirus-fears |title=Two men in quarantine in Samoa over coronavirus fears |date=28 January 2020 |work=Radio New Zealand |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127215814/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/408269/two-men-in-quarantine-in-samoa-over-coronavirus-fears |archive-date=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12303785 |title=Two men in quarantine in Samoa over virus fears |date=27 January 2020 |work=The New Zealand Herald |access-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211023357/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=12303785 |archive-date=11 February 2020 |issn=1170-0777}}</ref> Three students and a former student were evacuated{{when|date=February 2020}} with assistance from New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/update-samoan-students-in-wuhan-china/ |title=Samoan students in Wuhan, China \u2013 Government of Samoa |last=Tamaalii |first=Funefe'ai Dikaiosune Atoa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222140810/http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/update-samoan-students-in-wuhan-china/ |archive-date=22 February 2020 |access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On 9 February, eight Samoan nationals travelling from India were denied entry into the country after catching a connecting flight in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dreaver |first=Barbara |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/world/samoan-coronavirus-restrictions-see-eight-citizens-refused-entry-after-flying-through-singapore |title=Samoan coronavirus restrictions see eight citizens refused entry after flying through Singapore |date=15 February 2020 |work=[[TVNZ]] |access-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229235452/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/world/samoan-coronavirus-restrictions-see-eight-citizens-refused-entry-after-flying-through-singapore |archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, Samoa banned all [[cruise ship]]s from visiting the country.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410113/samoa-places-blanket-ban-on-cruise-ship-visits |title=Samoa places blanket ban on cruise ship visits |date=22 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222215027/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/410113/samoa-places-blanket-ban-on-cruise-ship-visits |archive-date=22 February 2020 |agency=Radio New Zealand}}</ref> On 29 February, the government announced restrictions on air travel, with the frequency of international flights into Samoa being reduced from 2 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/special-health-travel-advisory-in-relation-to-the-2019-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Special health travel advisory in relation to the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) |last=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 February 2020 |publisher=Government of Samoa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229235455/http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/02/special-health-travel-advisory-in-relation-to-the-2019-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ |archive-date=29 February 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Samoa reported its first suspected case of the coronavirus, an individual who had traveled from New Zealand. Bodily samples from the person were taken to [[Melbourne]] for testing.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tamaaliii |first1=Funefe'ai |title=Ministry of Health Coronavirus (COVID-19) Update 18/03/2020 |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/03/ministry-of-health-coronavirus-covid-19-update-18-03-2020/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=Government of Samoa |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 10-20 day wait for Samoa test result |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412091/coronavirus-10-20-day-wait-for-samoa-test-result |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> In response, the Samoan Government required all travelers including Samoan citizens to undergo a medical checkup upon returning.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tamaalii |first1=Funefe'ia |title=UPDATED TRAVEL ADVISORY NOVEL CORONAVIRUS (COVID-2019) |url=http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/03/updated-travel-advisory-novel-coronavirus-covid-2019-2/ |publisher=Government of Samoa |accessdate=19 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200319072542/http://www.samoagovt.ws/2020/03/updated-travel-advisory-novel-coronavirus-covid-2019-2/ |archivedate=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, Samoa declared a state of emergency, closing its borders to all but returning citizens.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tonga and Samoa declare states of emergency because of Covid-19 |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412240/tonga-and-samoa-declare-states-of-emergency-because-of-covid-19 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the Samoan Health Ministry confirmed that eight suspected cases of the coronavirus were being tested. All of these individuals had a prior history of travel or contact with relatives who traveled abroad.<ref>{{cite news |title=Eight suspected cases of coronavirus under investigation in Samoa |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/world/eight-suspected-cases-coronavirus-under-investigation-in-samoa |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[1 News]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kerr |first1=Florence |title=Coronavirus: Samoa tests eight suspected cases of Covid-19 |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120468609/coronavirus-samoa-tests-eight-suspected-cases-of-covid19 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Prime Minister of Samoa|Prime Minister]] [[Tuilaepa Aiono Sailele Malielegaoi]] announced that the first suspected case of COVID-19 had been cleared of the virus. While he confirmed that six of the eight suspected cases had tested negative for the coronavirus, they were still awaiting test results for the remaining two patients from New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news |title=Test for suspected Covid-19 case in Samoa comes back negative |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412317/test-for-suspected-covid-19-case-in-samoa-comes-back-negative |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> That same day, Samoa also suspended air travel with Australia and restricted flights from New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kerr |first1=Florence |title=Coronavirus: Samoa suspends all flights from Australia |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120472548/coronavirus-samoa-suspends-all-flights-from-australia |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, it was reported that a total of seven suspected cases of the coronavirus were awaiting testing in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news |title=Samoa waits for seven COVID-19 tests |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412513/samoa-waits-for-seven-covid-19-tests |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324091730/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412513/samoa-waits-for-seven-covid-19-tests |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Prime Minister Tuila'epa Sa'ilele Malielegaoi announced that individuals that didn't adhere to the COVID-19 restriction will be fined.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412587/samoa-to-fine-people-who-don-t-adhere-to-covid-19-restrictions|title=Samoa to fine people who don't adhere to Covid-19 restrictions|date=2020-03-25|work=[[Radio New Zealand]]|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On 26 March, the Samoan Government introduced lockdown measures including banning fishing boats from entering Samoa and fining businesses that breached the quarantine. Only cargo ships carrying goods and petrol will be allowed to enter Samoa.<ref>{{cite news |title=Samoa officially on lock down |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412647/samoa-officially-on-lock-down |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Solomon Islands===\nAs of 28 March, there have been no cases. As a precautionary measure the government has stepped up checks on incoming visitors, and introduced restrictions on visitors who have visited countries deemed high risk.<ref name=\"rnzPacific 16 March 2020\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411869/pacific-nations-take-further-measures-against-coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |website=RNZ |url-status=live|title=Pacific nations take further measures against coronavirus|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March Prime Minister [[Manasseh Sogavare]] suspended all flights into the country, and declared a precautionary state of emergency in [[Honiara]], by which most entertainment venues would be closed (churches are exempt from the order).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412792/covid-19-solomons-closes-borders-honiara-now-emergency-zone |website=RNZ |url-status=live|title=Covid-19: Solomons closes borders, Honiara now emergency zone|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, Franco Rodie, the permanent secretary of the [[Ministry of Education and Human Resources Development]], ordered the closure of all schools in the Solomon Islands.<ref>{{cite news |title=All schools ordered to close in Solomon Islands |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/413013/all-schools-ordered-to-close-in-solomon-islands |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Tonga===\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in the country. As a precautionary measure, various travel and quarantining restrictions have been put in place.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Cruise ships and yachts have also been banned from docking in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://matangitonga.to/2020/03/17/tonga-toughens-travel-advisory |title=Tonga toughens travel advisory |date=17 March 2020 |website=Matangi Tonga |url-status=live|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March Prime Minister [[Pohiva Tu'i'onetoa]] announced that the country would be under a lock-down 29 March-5 April.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412708/tonga-declares-lockdown-starting-this-weekend |title=Tonga declares lockdown starting this weekend |website=RNZ |date=27 March 2020|url-status=live|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Tuvalu===\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in the country. As a precautionary measure, visitors will not be allowed to land without first undergoing 14 days of isolation in a third party state.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> Circa 26 March the acting governor general declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412625/covid-19-pacific-summary|title=Covid-19: Pacific summary|date=2020-03-26|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n====Pitcairn Islands====\nAs of 28 March, there have been no cases in the British territory. As a precautionary measure, all passenger services to the islands have been suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.visitpitcairn.pn/index.html|title=Pitcairn Islands Tourism|website=Pitcairn Islands Tourism|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n====American Samoa====\nAs of 24 March, the US territory has not had any cases. On 6 March, the American Samoan government introduced new entry restrictions including restricting flight numbers and requiring travelers from Hawaii to spend 14 days in Hawaii and obtain a health clearance from health authorities.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Samoa tightens entry requirements over Covid-19 |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411111/american-samoa-tightens-entry-requirements-over-covid-19 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=6 March 2020}}</ref> On 11 March, a government task-force was set up to deal with the virus and quarantining measures have been put in place for incoming visitors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411472/american-samoa-establishes-covid-19-govt-taskforce |title=American Samoa establishes Covid-19 govt taskforce|access-date=17 March 2020|work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, half of the 210 passengers on a returning [[Hawaiian Airlines]] flight were required to self-quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Half of flight's passengers to self-quarantine in American Samoa |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411725/half-of-flight-s-passengers-to-self-quarantine-in-american-samoa |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Following a trip to the US mainland, Governor [[Lolo Matalasi Moliga]] self-isolated as a precautionary measure on 16 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/411793/covid-19-american-samoa-governor-self-isolates-as-a-precaution |title=Covid-19: American Samoa governor self-isolates as a precaution|access-date=17 March 2020|work=[[Radio New Zealand]]|date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, [[Iulogologo Joseph Pereir]]a, executive assistant to the American Samoa Governor and the head of the territory's coronavirus task force, acknowledged that the territory did not have facilities to test samples of the Covid-19 virus, having to rely on testing facilities in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Georgiev |first1=Peter |last2=Kaplan |first2=Adiel |title=American Samoa's coronavirus conundrum: No way to test |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-care/american-samoa-s-coronavirus-conundrum-no-way-test-n1167776 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vanuatu===\nAs of 28 March 2020, there have been no cases in the country. Travel restrictions and quarantine measures have been put in place for those entering the country.<ref name=\"rnzPacific 16 March 2020\"/> On 22 March, Vanuatu's health authorities confirmed that tests for a resort worker with a suspected case of coronavirus had returned negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19 tests in Samoa, Vanuatu come back negative |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412317/covid-19-tests-in-samoa-vanuatu-come-back-negative |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=22 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324091322/https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412317/covid-19-tests-in-samoa-vanuatu-come-back-negative |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March President [[Tallis Obed Moses]] declared a state of emergency in the country.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news |title=Vanuatu declares State of Emergency over Covid-19 |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412660/vanuatu-declares-state-of-emergency-over-covid-19 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> A tourist on a cruise ship visiting the island of [[Aneityum]] had tested positive for the virus, prompting a lockdown on the island.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Oceania]]\n*[[Bubonic plague]] Four deaths in [[Fremantle]], Western Australia, 1903\n*[[Smallpox]] Epidemic in News South Wales, Australia, 1828 \n*[[Influenza]] \n*[[Measles]] 40,000 died in 1875 Fiji Measles outbreak\n*[[Spanish flu]] 1918 flu pandemic, killed 17 to 50 million people worldwide\n*[[Epidemiology of HIV/AIDS|HIV/AIDS pandemic]]\n*[[2019 Samoa measles outbreak]] 83 deaths\n*[[2019\u20132020 dengue fever epidemic]] 276 cases and one death were reported in the Marshall Islands<ref>[https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/398139/marshalls-confirms-first-dengue-death Marshalls confirms first dengue death] by Giff Johnson, RNZ, 5 Sep 2019, retrieved 27 Mar 2020</ref> Outbreaks were also reported in Palau, the Federated States of Micronesia, the Cook Islands, Tuvalu, and the Philippines.<ref>[https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/397502/who-says-2019-worse-than-usual-for-dengue-in-pacific WHO says 2019 'worse than usual' for dengue in Pacific] RNZ, 26 Aug 2019, retrieved 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n{{End div col}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Update Live |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/coronavirus-updates-live-covid-19-cases-surpass-800-000-worldwide-nsw-and-qld-border-force-officials-test-positive-20200331-p54ft0.html |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/ ncov \u2013 CSSE] - Map of the expansion of the virus in Europe and in the world\n*[https://www.health.gov.au/news/health-alerts/novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov-health-alert/coronavirus-covid-19-current-situation-and-case-numbers Department of Health] - Case numbers as confirmed by the Australian government\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by continent|Oceania]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Oceania|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Oceania]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "Hugo999", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNew Zealand", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Oceania"}
